{"title_page": "Honkai Impact 3rd", "text_new": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Honkai Impact 3rd\n| image = \n| developer = [[miHoYo]]\n| publisher = \n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| writer = \n| composer = \n| series = ''Honkai''\n| platforms = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = {{vgrelease|[[PRC|CN]]|October 14, 2016|TW|May 18, 2017|[[Japan|JP]]|February 22, 2017|[[South Korea|KR]]|October 17, 2017|[[Southeast Asia|SEA]]|November, 2017|[[North America|NA]] and [[EU]]|March 28, 2018}}\n| genre = [[Action role-playing]], [[hack and slash]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Honkai Impact 3rd'''''  (Chinese: \u5d29\u574f3) is a [[free-to-play]] [[3D computer graphics|3D]] [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing]] [[mobile game]] developed by [[miHoYo]]. It is the third entry in the ''Houkai'' series and [[spiritual successor]] to ''Houkai Gakuen'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.fangcun.gg.en.aisa&hl=en_US|title=Guns Girl - Honkai Gakuen - Apps on Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> using many characters from the previous title in a separate story. The game is notable for incorporating a variety of genres from [[hack and slash]] and [[Social simulation game|social simulation]] to elements of [[bullet hell]], [[Platform game|platforming]], [[shoot 'em up]] and [[dungeon crawl]]ing across multiple single and multiplayer modes.\n\nIn addition to the mobile game, the storyline of ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' spans multiple supplementary media including an anime series,<ref>{{Citation|title=Cooking with Valkyries|url=https://myanimelist.net/anime/40100/Cooking_with_Valkyries|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> multiple [[manhua]] series,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://manga.honkaiimpact3.com/|title=Honkai Impact 3rd|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9/12/2019}}</ref> and promotional videos.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Honkai Impact 3rd'' has players control a team of up to three characters, known as \"Valkyries\", in real-time combat against various enemies. During battle, players may freely move their character around the battlefield and switch between their three deployed Valkyries to adapt to various enemy types. Each Valkyrie has unique attack, evasion, switch, and ultimate skills, as well as a [[rock-paper-scissors]]-based character type to fulfill different team roles. Valkyrie stats and skills can be customized with various weapons and equipment, which can be improved by using in-game resources. New equipment (known as \"Stigmata\"), weapons, and Valkyries can obtained either through in-game crafting or through a [[Gacha game|gacha]] system.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nSingle-player game modes include the \"Story\" campaign, consisting of short stages punctuated by dialogue in [[cutscene]]s and [[full motion video]]s (FMVs), \"Chronicles\", a series of brief side stories that explore Valkyries' backstories, and \"Open World\", allowing exploration of a large open-ended field to gather materials and complete various challenge tasks, coupled with its own storyline. The game features various multiplayer cooperative and competitive modes such as \"Co-Op Raid\", where players team up to unlock legendary weapons; \"Memorial Arena\", where players compete against a set of bosses for the highest score; and \"Dirac Sea\", where players attempt to progress as far as possible through a gauntlet of battles to compete for high scores. Players are able to join groups of other players, called \"Armadas\", which allow for more opportunities for events and rewards. Armadas allow for limited requesting of materials and resources from other players in the Armada.\n\nOutside of battles, ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' allows players to interact with the Valkyrie and Stigmata characters through the \"Dorm\" mode. Upon completing character specific tasks, different characters may be able to move into the dorms, whereupon new character information and dialogues between those characters can be seen. Players can craft various pieces of furniture and design the layout of the dorm rooms to increase the \"comfort\" of the Valkyries and Stigmata therein. Greater comfort levels allow players to level up their dorm limits for more elaborate decoration. Players are able to visit and view each other's decorated dorm layouts.\n\nSecondary gameplay mechanics include various [[minigame]]s incorporating [[bullet hell]], [[Platform game|platforming]], and [[shoot 'em up]] elements that allow players to gather various crafting and experience materials. Limited-time seasonal events may also include gameplay styles such as [[Dungeon crawl|dungeon crawling]] and [[Battle royale game|battle royale]] which are not normally seen in the main gameplay modes.\n\n==Plot==\n\n=== Setting ===\n''Honkai Impact 3rd'' is set in an alternate version of Earth, plagued by catastrophes resulting from \"Honkai\" (roughly translates to \"the collapse\"). Honkai is largely viewed as a malevolent force with a will of its own, able to corrupt humans into undead creatures, manifest itself in the form of various monsters, and select various individuals known as \"Herrschers\" to imbue with god-like powers able to trigger apocalyptic events. The Honkai is a cyclic phenomenon, returning to end civilization on Earth each time it gets too advanced - the Previous Era ended 50,000 years prior to the game's start, after the 14th Herrscher defeated humanity.  \n\nIn the present day, various global factions exist to combat or take advantage of the power of Honkai. These include \"Schicksal\", a European-based peace keeping organization that deploys human warriors known as Valkyries to combat the Honkai; \"Anti-Entropy\", formerly the North American branch of Schicksal that objected to the use of human soldiers in favor of mechanized robots; and \"World Serpent\", a shadow organization manipulating events since the end of the Previous Era. \n\nPrior to the story's start, three Herrscher awakenings (or \"Impacts\") have occurred in the Current Era: the Herrscher of Reason who became the leader of Anti-Entropy instead of fighting humanity, the Herrscher of the Void who was sealed away by Schicksal under mysterious circumstances, and the Herrscher of Lightning who was prevented from fully awakening and sent to train her powers as a Valkyrie at Schicksal's St.Freya school.   \n\n=== Story ===\n{{plot|date=April 2020}}\nThe storyline of ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' spans multiple supplementary media including an anime series,<ref>{{Citation|title=Cooking with Valkyries|url=https://myanimelist.net/anime/40100/Cooking_with_Valkyries|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> multiple [[manhua]] series,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://manga.honkaiimpact3.com/|title=Honkai Impact 3rd|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9/12/2019}}</ref> and promotional videos.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe game's story starts with three Valkyries-in-training (Kiana Kaslana, Mei Raiden, and Bronya Zaychik) boarding the ''Selene'', a hostile flying battleship. The three take control of the battleship, then subdue Bronya when she is abruptly controlled malevolently. Following the successful mission, the girls take a graduation exam, during which a mysterious voice contacts Kiana and informs her of her lost parents, Siegfried Kaslana and Cecilia Schariac.\n\nThe Valkyries then dispatch to Schicksal's Oceania Branch to recover the Gem of Desire following a local Honkai Eruption that decimated the area. The trio discovers Wendy, who was implanted with the Gem of Desire, and learn that Wendy triggered the Honkai Eruption due to a hatred of Schicksal, which had crippled Wendy. Bronya is controlled again and attacks, causing Wendy to transform into a Herrscher. Although Mei and Kiana are able to subdue both girls, Anti-Entropy forces appear and Bronya kidnaps Wendy and Mei. The Valkyries subsequently track Anti-Entropy to the hijacked ME Corp with Bronya's assistance. There, Bronya destroys the biochip in her brain to free herself from Cocolia's control and enable the Valkyries to escape, but leaving Wendy behind.\n\nSearching for a way to revive Bronya, Theresa Apocalypse creates a virtual datascape to find data on the biochip. Kiana is transported to a recreation of Siberia during the year 2000 in the midst of the 2nd Honkai War. Kiana meets virtual recreations of her parents, Siegfried and Cecilia, and while Siegfried is badly injured, Kiana and Cecilia team up and successfully defeat a recreation of 2nd Herrscher, Sirin. Upon Sirin's defeat, it is revealed that the events that Kiana experienced were a hallucination created from Kiana's desires by Sirin. Fu Hua captures Kiana and takes her to Schicksal HQ.\n\nTheresa, Mei, and Himeko ally with Anti-Entropy forces and storm Schicksal HQ to save Kiana, breaching its defenses with the ''Selene'' and the ''Hyperion''. While the Valkyries are successful in infiltrating Schicksal HQ, Rita Rossweisse and Fu Hua captures Himeko and Tesla. Otto Apocalypse successfully reawakens Sirin using Kiana's body as a host. Sirin dispatches Mei, Theresa, and the Anti-Entropy forces and engages Fu Hua in combat, stealing the 3rd Herrscher's power in the process. Himeko and Tesla, with Fu Hua's help, obtain a vial of anti-Honkai serum and a prototype Battlesuit imbued with a Herrscher's power. Himeko dons the Battlesuit and engages Sirin, fighting her to a standstill. Einstein uses the ''Selene''<nowiki/>'s cannon on Sirin, forcing her to retreat into \"Imaginary Space\" with Himeko being pulled in as well. Himeko duels with Sirin in the Imaginary Space and injects the anti-Honkai serum into Sirin, causing her to revert to Kiana. Suffering massive losses, the remaining Valkyries and Anti-Entropy retreat, and the world is left devastated in the wake of Sirin's attack. Himeko and Kiana both go missing.\n\nFour months after Sirin's attack, Mei, Theresa, and Bronya attempt to meet with an intel dealer named Gray Serpent in Arc City who claims to have seen the Herrscher of the Void, unaware that Otto Apocalypse had dispatched Rita to obtain his information as well. Rita seems to kill Gray Serpent and steals his cybernetic implants, leading the Valkyries to capture a cyborg girl called the Ningyo. Before they can extract the Ningyo's information, Rita intercepts the Valkyries, steals the data, and formats the Ningyo's memory. While Einstein and Tesla attempt to retrieve the Ningyo's lost memories, the team is contacted by Cocolia, who convinces them to help find the Gem of Desire. Gray Serpent, seeking payment for the Valkyrie's theft of the Ningyo, hacks into the ''Selene''. When Bronya follows Gray Serpent into virtual space, he traps Bronya in a data labyrinth formed from her memories to deter her. Bronya is able to escape, though she witnesses a record of the 1st Herrscher, Welt Young, and Einstein battling the World Serpent, who is sealed within the Sea of Quanta.\n\nBronya, Theresa, and Einstein travel to The Deep, where Bronya is reunited with Cocolia and childhood friends Rosalia and Liliya. Cocolia informs the trio that the Gem of Desire was lost in the Sea of Quanta, and must be retrieved. While Einstein prepares to enter the Eye of the Deep, a portal leading to the Sea of Quanta, Bronya attempts to reconcile with Cocolia. When Einstein discovers Cocolia scheming with Gray Serpent, Gray Serpent attacks Einstein and she vanishes. A swarm of Honkai emerges from the Eye of the Deep and attacks, leading Bronya to dive into the Sea of Quanta alone. In the Sea, Bronya is greeted by Joachim, a fragment of Welt Young. Joachim sends Bronya to multiple pocket universes as a test, during which Bronya is reunited with Seele Vollerei (Bronya's childhood friend who became stuck in quantum state following a failed X-10 Project years ago). In efforts to guide Seele out of the quanta, they resolve to escape together.\n\nAfter clearing some honkai beasts and being separated, Seele and Bronya reunite and try to escape the labyrinth.The two girls reach the edge of the Quanta but are caught by tentacles. Bronya makes a sacrifice and cuts the tentacles binding Seele, succumbing to the tentacles herself. However, Seele dislikes her powerlessness and the Dark Seele finally agreesto lend her power to Seele, and they use their combined power to rescue Bronya.\n\nBack to Kiana; after recapturing control of her body, she has been living in exile alone in the Arc City in order not to hurt others with the Herrscher personality. One night, she is fighting with Honkai beasts when Sirin seeks the opportunity to torment and brainwash Kiana, attempting to reawake the Herrscher. Fortunately, Fu Hua reaches Kiana's mind and drive Sirin away. Kiana holds hatred towards Fu Hua at first, but Fu Hua tells Kiana that their spirits are combined forever due to the power of Key of Deity, and that Kiana must learn to control the Herrscher power by herself. Under Fu Hua's training, Kiana finally succeeds, and returns to fighting against Honkai in Arc City.\n\n==Development==\nThe production team for ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' grew from a 7-person start to employing over 200 employees in 2018.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bilibili.com/read/cv1141716/|title=\u5d29\u574f3\u4e0a\u7ebf\u4e24\u5e74 \u8001\u73a9\u5bb6\u4eec\u7684\u8bc4\u4ef7\u96c6\u9526|last=\u6bcf\u65e5\u6e38\u620f\u83cc|website=www.bilibili.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> [[Mihoyo]] offers small amounts of in-game currency to users that fill out surveys about their experience in the game, allowing the game's [[Developer (software)|developers]] to adjust future events and tweak the game. As a result, ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' is under a continuous-update system, [[Patch (computing)|patch]]ing [[Software bug|bug]] fixes and changing or adding content multiple times per year. The game has had many significant changes since launch, including rewriting the entire first two chapters of the story in a December 2018 update.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honkaiimpact3.gamepedia.com/Update_Log|title=Update Log|website=Honkai Impact 3 Wiki|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> The developers stated that their decision to make ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' be in the [[free-to-play]] [[monetization]] system (rather than a [[Premium business model|premium]], or paid, game) with the purpose of making the game more available to players.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/interview/68023/the-making-of-mihoyos-honkai-impact-3rd/|title=Hack and slash: The making of MIHOYO's Honkai Impact 3rd|last=Harris|first=Iain|last2=Writer|first2=Staff|website=pocketgamer.biz|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> [[Devil May Cry]] and [[Bayonetta]] significantly affected the game makers' ideas for the [[Gameplay|fight system]] of ''Honkai Impact 3rd''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honkaiimpact3.gamepedia.com/Honkai_Impact_3_Wiki|title=Honkai Impact 3 Wiki|website=Honkai Impact 3 Wiki|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nAfter a few years of users emulating ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' on computers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bluestacks.com/blog/game-guides/honkai-impact-3.html|title=Honkai Impact 3rd \u2013 Bluestacks \u2013 The Best Android Emulator on PC as Rated by You|website=Bluestacks - The Best Android Emulator on PC as Rated by You|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.memuplay.com/how-to-play-Honkai-Impact-3rd-on-pc.html|title=Download Honkai Impact 3rd on PC with MEmu|website=Memu Android Emulator|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and an update making emulation more difficult, the game's official PC version was developed, releasing to the public on December 26th, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com/global/en-us/news/1851|title=Honkai Impact 3rd PC Version Launches on December 26!|website=honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n===Manga===\n''Honkai Impact 3rd'' features an ongoing serialized manhua of the same name in Chinese<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://comic.benghuai.com/book|title=\u5d29\u574f\u6f2b\u753b}}</ref> and in English.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mangadex.org/title/22297/honkai-impact-3rd|title=Mangadex}}</ref> The manga begins before Chapter 1 of the main game story arc that aims to supplement and flesh out the in-game plot, and often includes character origins. Several in-game battlesuits worn by the Valkyries are illustrated in the manga as well. The Manga has three prequel titles and one main title.\n\n==Reception==\nThe game first attracted a large fanbase in Asia before spreading globally: first released in [[China]] in late 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bh3.com/index.php/news/13|title=\u5d29\u574f\u6218\u5f79\uff0c\u7edd\u5730\u51fa\u51fb\uff01\u300a\u5d29\u574f3\u300b\u5168\u5e73\u53f0\u516c\u6d4b\u4f5c\u6218\u6307\u4ee4}}</ref> it reached 1 million downloads in Japan 11 days after release, and [[IGN]] reported that ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' gathered a total of 35 million downloads worldwide as of March 28, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/28/honkai-impact-3rd-big-in-japan-coming-to-america|title=HONKAI IMPACT 3RD: BIG IN JAPAN, COMING TO AMERICA|date=March 28, 2018|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref> The game has been released in Korea, Taiwan, Southeast Asia, North America, and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/interview/68023/the-making-of-mihoyos-honkai-impact-3rd/%E2%80%98/|title=Hack and slash: The making of MIHOYO's Honkai Impact 3rd}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/67912/honkai-impact-3rd-racks-up-35m-downloads/|title=New mobile RPG Honkai Impact 3rd racks up 35 million downloads}}</ref> and supports multiple languages including Simplified Chinese, Traditional Chinese,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/0/147140.html|title=3D \u52d5\u4f5c\u624b\u6a5f\u904a\u6232\u300a\u5d29\u58de 3rd\u300b\u7e41\u9ad4\u4e2d\u6587\u7248\u4eca\u65e5\u65bc\u96d9\u5e73\u53f0\u958b\u653e\u4e0b\u8f09}}</ref> English,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerbraves.com/honkai-impact-3rd-is-now-available-worldwide/|title=Honkai Impact 3rd Is Now Available Worldwide!}}</ref> Japanese,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/366/G036683/20170217004/|title=\u6226\u4e59\u5973\u305f\u3061\u306e3D\u30a2\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u300c\u5d29\u58ca3rd\u300d\u304c\u914d\u4fe1\u958b\u59cb\u3002\"\u8056\u75d5\u51ac\u306e\u304a\u59eb\u69d8\"\u3092\u3082\u3089\u3048\u308b\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u8a18\u5ff5\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u306f3\u67082\u65e5\u307e\u3067\u958b\u50ac}}</ref> Korean,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inven.co.kr/webzine/news/?news=187408&site=honkai3rd|title=[\ub274\uc2a4] \ud788\ud398\ub9ac\uc628\ud638 \uc791\uc804 \uac1c\uc2dc! '\ubd95\uad34 3rd' \uad6d\ub0b4 \uc815\uc2dd \ucd9c\uc2dc}}</ref> Vietnamese,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamek.vn/honkai-impact-3-chinh-thuc-mo-cua-tai-dna-ho-tro-ca-ngon-ngu-tieng-viet-2017110118275755.chn|title=Honkai Impact 3 ch\u00ednh th\u1ee9c m\u1edf c\u1eeda t\u1ea1i \u0110N\u00c1, h\u1ed7 tr\u1ee3 c\u1ea3 ng\u00f4n ng\u1eef ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t}}</ref> Thai,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisgamethailand.com/content/Honkai-Impact-3-%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%A1%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%94%E0%B9%83%E0%B8%AB%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B9%83%E0%B8%99%E0%B9%82%E0%B8%8B%E0%B8%99-SEA.html|title=\u0e04\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e40\u0e1f\u0e34\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e21! Honkai Impact 3 \u0e40\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e21\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e43\u0e19\u0e42\u0e0b\u0e19 SEA}}</ref> French,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/news/993261/honkai-impact-3rd-le-jeu-evenement-debarque-en-france.htm|title=News jeu Honkai Impact 3rd : Le jeu \u00e9v\u00e9nement d\u00e9barque en France !}}</ref> German, and Indonesian.\n\nBesides when it released and when the official PC version was created, little media focus has been on ''Honkai Impact 3rd''. The continual updates and overhauls to ''Honkai Impact 3rd'''s events and mechanics make many of the reviews written (when the game released) inaccurate representations of the gameplay and quality of the game presently. Reviews say that the game has changed through ups and downs as it tweaked its system and tested in-game events to be ultimately more engaging and enjoyable.<ref name=\":02\" /> Similarly, many article guides exist for gameplay elements that no longer exist within the game, such as the base. The majority of recent articles (as of March 2020) concerning or mentioning ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' either announce its PC release, or mention it while featuring [[Genshin Impact]], Mihoyo's upcoming release. \n\nIn an article from 2017, ''Ungeek.com'' says that the game has some later-game systems that are unintuitive, and cites the large download size for a mobile game as a negative.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ungeek.ph/2017/11/honkai-impact-3-review-taking-mobile-anime-games-to-a-whole-new-level/|title=Honkai Impact 3 Review {{!}} Taking Mobile Anime Games to a Whole New Level!|last=Ki-Chan|first=Cosplayer|date=2017-11-28|website=Ungeek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The review praised the game's visual quality and the ease of learning to play the game, as well as the overall quality of the game, and positively recommended it.<ref name=\":22\" /> The article mentioned that the quality of the game was comparable to console games.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com/asia Official Asian website]\n* [https://honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com/global Official global website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Honkai Impact 3rd}}\n[[Category:2016 video games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Gacha games]]\n[[Category:Mobile games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Honkai Impact 3rd\n| image = \n| developer = [[miHoYo]]\n| publisher = \n| engine = [[Unity (game engine)|Unity]]\n| director = \n| producer = \n| designer = \n| programmer = \n| artist = \n| writer = \n| composer = \n| series = ''Honkai''\n| platforms = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]], [[Microsoft Windows]]\n| released = {{vgrelease|[[PRC|CN]]|October 14, 2016|TW|May 18, 2017|[[Japan|JP]]|February 22, 2017|[[South Korea|KR]]|October 17, 2017|[[Southeast Asia|SEA]]|November, 2017|[[North America|NA]] and [[EU]]|March 28, 2018}}\n| genre = [[Action role-playing]], [[hack and slash]]\n| modes = [[Single-player]], [[multiplayer]]\n}}\n\n'''''Honkai Impact 3rd'''''  (Chinese: \u5d29\u574f3) is a [[free-to-play]] [[3D computer graphics|3D]] [[Action role-playing game|action role-playing]] [[mobile game]] developed by [[miHoYo]]. It is the third entry in the ''Houkai'' series and [[spiritual successor]] to ''Houkai Gakuen'',<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=com.fangcun.gg.en.aisa&hl=en_US|title=Guns Girl - Honkai Gakuen - Apps on Google Play|website=play.google.com|language=en|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> using many characters from the previous title in a separate story. The game is notable for incorporating a variety of genres from [[hack and slash]] and [[Social simulation game|social simulation]] to elements of [[bullet hell]], [[Platform game|platforming]], [[shoot 'em up]] and [[dungeon crawl]]ing across multiple single and multiplayer modes.\n\nIn addition to the mobile game, the storyline of ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' spans multiple supplementary media including an anime series,<ref>{{Citation|title=Cooking with Valkyries|url=https://myanimelist.net/anime/40100/Cooking_with_Valkyries|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> multiple [[manhua]] series,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://manga.honkaiimpact3.com/|title=Honkai Impact 3rd|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9/12/2019}}</ref> and promotional videos.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Honkai Impact 3rd'' has players control a team of up to three characters, known as \"Valkyries\", in real-time combat against various enemies. During battle, players may freely move their character around the battlefield and switch between their three deployed Valkyries to adapt to various enemy types. Each Valkyrie has unique attack, evasion, switch, and ultimate skills, as well as a [[rock-paper-scissors]]-based character type to fulfill different team roles. Valkyrie stats and skills can be customized with various weapons and equipment, which can be improved by using in-game resources. New equipment (known as \"Stigmata\"), weapons, and Valkyries can obtained either through in-game crafting or through a [[Gacha game|gacha]] system.{{Citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\nSingle-player game modes include the \"Story\" campaign, consisting of short stages punctuated by dialogue in [[cutscene]]s and [[full motion video]]s (FMVs), \"Chronicles\", a series of brief side stories that explore Valkyries' backstories, and \"Open World\", allowing exploration of a large open-ended field to gather materials and complete various challenge tasks, coupled with its own storyline. The game features various multiplayer cooperative and competitive modes such as \"Co-Op Raid\", where players team up to unlock legendary weapons; \"Memorial Arena\", where players compete against a set of bosses for the highest score; and \"Dirac Sea\", where players attempt to progress as far as possible through a gauntlet of battles to compete for high scores. Players are able to join groups of other players, called \"Armadas\", which allow for more opportunities for events and rewards. Armadas allow for limited requesting of materials and resources from other players in the Armada.\n\nOutside of battles, ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' allows players to interact with the Valkyrie and Stigmata characters through the \"Dorm\" mode. Upon completing character specific tasks, different characters may be able to move into the dorms, whereupon new character information and dialogues between those characters can be seen. Players can craft various pieces of furniture and design the layout of the dorm rooms to increase the \"comfort\" of the Valkyries and Stigmata therein. Greater comfort levels allow players to level up their dorm limits for more elaborate decoration. Players are able to visit and view each other's decorated dorm layouts.\n\nSecondary gameplay mechanics include various [[minigame]]s incorporating [[bullet hell]], [[Platform game|platforming]], and [[shoot 'em up]] elements that allow players to gather various crafting and experience materials. Limited-time seasonal events may also include gameplay styles such as [[Dungeon crawl|dungeon crawling]] and [[Battle royale game|battle royale]] which are not normally seen in the main gameplay modes.\n\n==Plot==\n\n=== Setting ===\n''Honkai Impact 3rd'' is set in an alternate version of Earth, plagued by catastrophes resulting from \"Honkai\" (roughly translates to \"the collapse\"). Honkai is largely viewed as a malevolent force with a will of its own, able to corrupt humans into undead creatures, manifest itself in the form of various monsters, and select various individuals known as \"Herrschers\" to imbue with god-like powers able to trigger apocalyptic events. The Honkai is a cyclic phenomenon, returning to end civilization on Earth each time it gets too advanced - the Previous Era ended 50,000 years prior to the game's start, after the 14th Herrscher defeated humanity.  \n\nIn the present day, various global factions exist to combat or take advantage of the power of Honkai. These include \"Schicksal\", a European-based peace keeping organization that deploys human warriors known as Valkyries to combat the Honkai; \"Anti-Entropy\", formerly the North American branch of Schicksal that objected to the use of human soldiers in favor of mechanized robots; and \"World Serpent\", a shadow organization manipulating events since the end of the Previous Era. \n\nPrior to the story's start, three Herrscher awakenings (or \"Impacts\") have occurred in the Current Era: the Herrscher of Reason who became the leader of Anti-Entropy instead of fighting humanity, the Herrscher of the Void who was sealed away by Schicksal under mysterious circumstances, and the Herrscher of Lightning who was prevented from fully awakening and sent to train her powers as a Valkyrie at Schicksal's St.Freya school.   \n\n=== Story ===\n{{plot|date=April 2020}}\nThe storyline of ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' spans multiple supplementary media including an anime series,<ref>{{Citation|title=Cooking with Valkyries|url=https://myanimelist.net/anime/40100/Cooking_with_Valkyries|access-date=2019-09-13}}</ref> multiple [[manhua]] series,<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://manga.honkaiimpact3.com/|title=Honkai Impact 3rd|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=9/12/2019}}</ref> and promotional videos.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe game's story starts with three Valkyries-in-training (Kiana Kaslana, Mei Raiden, and Bronya Zaychik) boarding the ''Selene'', a hostile flying battleship. The three take control of the battleship, then subdue Bronya when she is abruptly controlled malevolently. Following the successful mission, the girls take a graduation exam, during which a mysterious voice contacts Kiana and informs her of her lost parents, Siegfried Kaslana and Cecilia Schariac.\n\nThe Valkyries then dispatch to Schicksal's Oceania Branch to recover the Gem of Desire following a local Honkai Eruption that decimated the area. The trio discovers Wendy, who was implanted with the Gem of Desire, and learn that Wendy triggered the Honkai Eruption due to a hatred of Schicksal, which had crippled Wendy. Bronya is controlled again and attacks, causing Wendy to transform into a Herrscher. Although Mei and Kiana are able to subdue both girls, Anti-Entropy forces appear and Bronya kidnaps Wendy and Mei. The Valkyries subsequently track Anti-Entropy to the hijacked ME Corp with Bronya's assistance. There, Bronya destroys the biochip in her brain to free herself from Cocolia's control and enable the Valkyries to escape, but leaving Wendy behind.\n\nSearching for a way to revive Bronya, Theresa Apocalypse creates a virtual datascape to find data on the biochip. Kiana is transported to a recreation of Siberia during the year 2000 in the midst of the 2nd Honkai War. Kiana meets virtual recreations of her parents, Siegfried and Cecilia, and while Siegfried is badly injured, Kiana and Cecilia team up and successfully defeat a recreation of 2nd Herrscher, Sirin. Upon Sirin's defeat, it is revealed that the events that Kiana experienced were a hallucination created from Kiana's desires by Sirin. Fu Hua captures Kiana and takes her to Schicksal HQ.\n\nTheresa, Mei, and Himeko ally with Anti-Entropy forces and storm Schicksal HQ to save Kiana, breaching its defenses with the ''Selene'' and the ''Hyperion''. While the Valkyries are successful in infiltrating Schicksal HQ, Rita Rossweisse and Fu Hua captures Himeko and Tesla. Otto Apocalypse successfully reawakens Sirin using Kiana's body as a host. Sirin dispatches Mei, Theresa, and the Anti-Entropy forces and engages Fu Hua in combat, stealing the 3rd Herrscher's power in the process. Himeko and Tesla, with Fu Hua's help, obtain a vial of anti-Honkai serum and a prototype Battlesuit imbued with a Herrscher's power. Himeko dons the Battlesuit and engages Sirin, fighting her to a standstill. Einstein uses the ''Selene''<nowiki/>'s cannon on Sirin, forcing her to retreat into \"Imaginary Space\" with Himeko being pulled in as well. Himeko duels with Sirin in the Imaginary Space and injects the anti-Honkai serum into Sirin, causing her to revert to Kiana. Suffering massive losses, the remaining Valkyries and Anti-Entropy retreat, and the world is left devastated in the wake of Sirin's attack. Himeko and Kiana both go missing.\n\nFour months after Sirin's attack, Mei, Theresa, and Bronya attempt to meet with an intel dealer named Gray Serpent in Arc City who claims to have seen the Herrscher of the Void, unaware that Otto Apocalypse had dispatched Rita to obtain his information as well. Rita seems to kill Gray Serpent and steals his cybernetic implants, leading the Valkyries to capture a cyborg girl called the Ningyo. Before they can extract the Ningyo's information, Rita intercepts the Valkyries, steals the data, and formats the Ningyo's memory. While Einstein and Tesla attempt to retrieve the Ningyo's lost memories, the team is contacted by Cocolia, who convinces them to help find the Gem of Desire. Gray Serpent, seeking payment for the Valkyrie's theft of the Ningyo, hacks into the ''Selene''. When Bronya follows Gray Serpent into virtual space, he traps Bronya in a data labyrinth formed from her memories to deter her. Bronya is able to escape, though she witnesses a record of the 1st Herrscher, Welt Young, and Einstein battling the World Serpent, who is sealed within the Sea of Quanta.\n\nBronya, Theresa, and Einstein travel to The Deep, where Bronya is reunited with Cocolia and childhood friends Rosalia and Liliya. Cocolia informs the trio that the Gem of Desire was lost in the Sea of Quanta, and must be retrieved. While Einstein prepares to enter the Eye of the Deep, a portal leading to the Sea of Quanta, Bronya attempts to reconcile with Cocolia. When Einstein discovers Cocolia scheming with Gray Serpent, Gray Serpent attacks Einstein and she vanishes. A swarm of Honkai emerges from the Eye of the Deep and attacks, leading Bronya to dive into the Sea of Quanta alone. In the Sea, Bronya is greeted by Joachim, a fragment of Welt Young. Joachim sends Bronya to multiple pocket universes as a test, during which Bronya is reunited with Seele Vollerei (Bronya's childhood friend who became stuck in quantum state following a failed X-10 Project years ago). In efforts to guide Seele out of the quanta, they resolve to escape together.\n\nAfter clearing some honkai beasts and being separated, Seele and Bronya reunite and try to escape the labyrinth.The two girls reach the edge of the Quanta but are caught by tentacles. Bronya makes a sacrifice and cuts the tentacles binding Seele, succumbing to the tentacles herself. However, Seele dislikes her powerlessness and the Dark Seele finally agreesto lend her power to Seele, and they use their combined power to rescue Bronya.\n\nBack to Kiana; after recapturing control of her body, she has been living in exile alone in the Arc City in order not to hurt others with the Herrscher personality. One night, she is fighting with Honkai beasts when Sirin seeks the opportunity to torment and brainwash Kiana, attempting to reawake the Herrscher. Fortunately, Fu Hua reaches Kiana's mind and drive Sirin away. Kiana holds hatred towards Fu Hua at first, but Fu Hua tells Kiana that their spirits are combined forever due to the power of Key of Deity, and that Kiana must learn to control the Herrscher power by herself. Under Fu Hua's training, Kiana finally succeeds, and returns to fighting against Honkai in Arc City.\n\n==Development==\nThe production team for ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' grew from a 7-person start to employing over 200 employees in 2018.<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bilibili.com/read/cv1141716/|title=\u5d29\u574f3\u4e0a\u7ebf\u4e24\u5e74 \u8001\u73a9\u5bb6\u4eec\u7684\u8bc4\u4ef7\u96c6\u9526|last=\u6bcf\u65e5\u6e38\u620f\u83cc|website=www.bilibili.com|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> [[Mihoyo]] offers small amounts of in-game currency to users that fill out surveys about their experience in the game, allowing the game's [[Developer (software)|developers]] to adjust future events and tweak the game. As a result, ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' is under a continuous-update system, [[Patch (computing)|patch]]ing [[Software bug|bug]] fixes and changing or adding content multiple times per year. The game has had many significant changes since launch, including rewriting the entire first two chapters of the story in a December 2018 update.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honkaiimpact3.gamepedia.com/Update_Log|title=Update Log|website=Honkai Impact 3 Wiki|language=en|access-date=2020-03-05}}</ref> The developers stated that their decision to make ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' be in the [[free-to-play]] [[monetization]] system (rather than a [[Premium business model|premium]], or paid, game) with the purpose of making the game more available to players.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/interview/68023/the-making-of-mihoyos-honkai-impact-3rd/|title=Hack and slash: The making of MIHOYO's Honkai Impact 3rd|last=Harris|first=Iain|last2=Writer|first2=Staff|website=pocketgamer.biz|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref> [[Devil May Cry]] and [[Bayonetta]] significantly affected the game makers' ideas for the [[Gameplay|fight system]] of ''Honkai Impact 3rd''.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honkaiimpact3.gamepedia.com/Honkai_Impact_3_Wiki|title=Honkai Impact 3 Wiki|website=Honkai Impact 3 Wiki|language=en|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\nAfter a few years of users emulating ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' on computers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bluestacks.com/blog/game-guides/honkai-impact-3.html|title=Honkai Impact 3rd \u2013 Bluestacks \u2013 The Best Android Emulator on PC as Rated by You|website=Bluestacks - The Best Android Emulator on PC as Rated by You|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.memuplay.com/how-to-play-Honkai-Impact-3rd-on-pc.html|title=Download Honkai Impact 3rd on PC with MEmu|website=Memu Android Emulator|language=en|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> and an update making emulation more difficult, the game's official PC version was developed, releasing to the public on December 26th, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com/global/en-us/news/1851|title=Honkai Impact 3rd PC Version Launches on December 26!|website=honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n\n===Manga===\n''Honkai Impact 3rd'' features an ongoing serialized manhua of the same name in Chinese<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://comic.benghuai.com/book|title=\u5d29\u574f\u6f2b\u753b}}</ref> and in English.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://mangadex.org/title/22297/honkai-impact-3rd|title=Mangadex}}</ref> The manga begins before Chapter 1 of the main game story arc that aims to supplement and flesh out the in-game plot, and often includes character origins. Several in-game battlesuits worn by the Valkyries are illustrated in the manga as well. The Manga has three prequel titles and one main title.\n\n==Reception==\nThe game first attracted a large fanbase in Asia before spreading globally: first released in [[China]] in late 2016,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bh3.com/index.php/news/13|title=\u5d29\u574f\u6218\u5f79\uff0c\u7edd\u5730\u51fa\u51fb\uff01\u300a\u5d29\u574f3\u300b\u5168\u5e73\u53f0\u516c\u6d4b\u4f5c\u6218\u6307\u4ee4}}</ref> it reached 1 million downloads in Japan 11 days after release, and [[IGN]] reported that ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' gathered a total of 35 million downloads worldwide as of March 28, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ign.com/articles/2018/03/28/honkai-impact-3rd-big-in-japan-coming-to-america|title=HONKAI IMPACT 3RD: BIG IN JAPAN, COMING TO AMERICA|date=March 28, 2018|work=[[IGN]]|accessdate=April 9, 2019}}</ref> The game has been released in Korea, Taiwan, Southeast Asia, North America, and Europe,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/interview/68023/the-making-of-mihoyos-honkai-impact-3rd/%E2%80%98/|title=Hack and slash: The making of MIHOYO's Honkai Impact 3rd}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.biz/asia/news/67912/honkai-impact-3rd-racks-up-35m-downloads/|title=New mobile RPG Honkai Impact 3rd racks up 35 million downloads}}</ref> and supports multiple languages including Simplified Chinese, Traditional Chinese,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gnn.gamer.com.tw/0/147140.html|title=3D \u52d5\u4f5c\u624b\u6a5f\u904a\u6232\u300a\u5d29\u58de 3rd\u300b\u7e41\u9ad4\u4e2d\u6587\u7248\u4eca\u65e5\u65bc\u96d9\u5e73\u53f0\u958b\u653e\u4e0b\u8f09}}</ref> English,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamerbraves.com/honkai-impact-3rd-is-now-available-worldwide/|title=Honkai Impact 3rd Is Now Available Worldwide!}}</ref> Japanese,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.4gamer.net/games/366/G036683/20170217004/|title=\u6226\u4e59\u5973\u305f\u3061\u306e3D\u30a2\u30af\u30b7\u30e7\u30f3\u300c\u5d29\u58ca3rd\u300d\u304c\u914d\u4fe1\u958b\u59cb\u3002\"\u8056\u75d5\u51ac\u306e\u304a\u59eb\u69d8\"\u3092\u3082\u3089\u3048\u308b\u30ea\u30ea\u30fc\u30b9\u8a18\u5ff5\u30a4\u30d9\u30f3\u30c8\u306f3\u67082\u65e5\u307e\u3067\u958b\u50ac}}</ref> Korean,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.inven.co.kr/webzine/news/?news=187408&site=honkai3rd|title=[\ub274\uc2a4] \ud788\ud398\ub9ac\uc628\ud638 \uc791\uc804 \uac1c\uc2dc! '\ubd95\uad34 3rd' \uad6d\ub0b4 \uc815\uc2dd \ucd9c\uc2dc}}</ref> Vietnamese,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gamek.vn/honkai-impact-3-chinh-thuc-mo-cua-tai-dna-ho-tro-ca-ngon-ngu-tieng-viet-2017110118275755.chn|title=Honkai Impact 3 ch\u00ednh th\u1ee9c m\u1edf c\u1eeda t\u1ea1i \u0110N\u00c1, h\u1ed7 tr\u1ee3 c\u1ea3 ng\u00f4n ng\u1eef ti\u1ebfng Vi\u1ec7t}}</ref> Thai,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thisisgamethailand.com/content/Honkai-Impact-3-%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%95%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B5%E0%B8%A2%E0%B8%A1%E0%B9%80%E0%B8%9B%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%94%E0%B9%83%E0%B8%AB%E0%B9%89%E0%B8%9A%E0%B8%A3%E0%B8%B4%E0%B8%81%E0%B8%B2%E0%B8%A3%E0%B9%83%E0%B8%99%E0%B9%82%E0%B8%8B%E0%B8%99-SEA.html|title=\u0e04\u0e2d\u0e19\u0e40\u0e1f\u0e34\u0e23\u0e4c\u0e21! Honkai Impact 3 \u0e40\u0e15\u0e23\u0e35\u0e22\u0e21\u0e40\u0e1b\u0e34\u0e14\u0e43\u0e2b\u0e49\u0e1a\u0e23\u0e34\u0e01\u0e32\u0e23\u0e43\u0e19\u0e42\u0e0b\u0e19 SEA}}</ref> French,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.jeuxvideo.com/news/993261/honkai-impact-3rd-le-jeu-evenement-debarque-en-france.htm|title=News jeu Honkai Impact 3rd : Le jeu \u00e9v\u00e9nement d\u00e9barque en France !}}</ref> German, and Indonesian.\n\nBesides when it released and when the official PC version was created, little media focus has been on ''Honkai Impact 3rd''. The continual updates and overhauls to ''Honkai Impact 3rd'''s events and mechanics make many of the reviews written (when the game released) inaccurate representations of the gameplay and quality of the game presently. Reviews say the the game has changed through ups and downs as it tweaked its system and tested in-game events to be ultimately more engaging and enjoyable.<ref name=\":02\" /> Similarly, many article guides exist for gameplay elements that no longer exist within the game, such as the base. The majority of recent articles (as of March 2020) concerning or mentioning ''Honkai Impact 3rd'' either announce its PC release, or mention it while featuring [[Genshin Impact]], Mihoyo's upcoming release. \n\nIn an article from 2017, ''Ungeek.com'' says that the game has some later-game systems that are unintuitive, and cites the large download size for a mobile game as a negative.<ref name=\":22\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ungeek.ph/2017/11/honkai-impact-3-review-taking-mobile-anime-games-to-a-whole-new-level/|title=Honkai Impact 3 Review {{!}} Taking Mobile Anime Games to a Whole New Level!|last=Ki-Chan|first=Cosplayer|date=2017-11-28|website=Ungeek|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-31}}</ref> The review praised the game's visual quality and the ease of learning to play the game, as well as the overall quality of the game, and positively recommended it.<ref name=\":22\" /> The article mentioned that the quality of the game was comparable to console games.<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":22\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com/asia Official Asian website]\n* [https://honkaiimpact3.mihoyo.com/global Official global website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Honkai Impact 3rd}}\n[[Category:2016 video games]]\n[[Category:Action role-playing video games]]\n[[Category:Gacha games]]\n[[Category:Mobile games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in China]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n", "name_user": "Arjayay", "label": "safe", "comment": "Duplicate word reworded", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Honkai_Impact_3rd"}
{"title_page": "Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System", "text_new": "{{short description|Automated flight control feature developed by Boeing, contributing to the 737 MAX crashes}}\n[[File:Trimmable horizontal stabiliser.JPG|thumb|Movable horizontal stabilizer on an [[Embraer ERJ-170]]]]\n\n<section begin=summary/>The <noinclude>'''</noinclude>{{No selflink|Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System}} (MCAS) <noinclude>'''</noinclude> is a [[flight control law]] (software) embedded into the [[Boeing 737 MAX]] [[flight control system]] which attempts to mimic [[Aircraft flight control system |pitching]] behavior similar to aircraft in the previous generation of the series, the [[Boeing 737 NG]]. When MCAS detects that the aircraft is operating in manual flight, with flaps up, at an elevated angle of attack (AoA), it adjusts the horizontal stabilizer trim to add positive force feedback (a \"nose heavy\" feel), through the control column, so the pilot will not inadvertently pull the airplane up too steeply, potentially causing a [[Stall (fluid dynamics)|stall]]. Contrary to descriptions in news reports, however, Boeing claims that MCAS is not an anti-stall system. Stabilizer movement commanded by MCAS pushes down the nose of the airplane automatically without pilot input.\n\nMCAS on the MAX was designed to activate using input from only one of the airplane's two angle of attack sensors, making the system susceptible to a [[single point of failure]]. Boeing omitted a description of MCAS from MAX flight manuals, leaving pilots unaware of the system when the airplane entered service.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laris |first1=Michael |title=Changes to flawed Boeing 737 Max were kept from pilots, DeFazio says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/changes-to-flawed-boeing-737-max-were-kept-from-pilots-defazio-says/2019/06/19/553522f0-92bc-11e9-aadb-74e6b2b46f6a_story.html |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=29 February 2020 |date=June 19, 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, Boeing admitted that MCAS played a role in the fatal crashes of [[Lion Air Flight 610]] and [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]]. The first time Boeing publicly revealed the existence of MCAS on the 737 MAX was in a message to airline operators and other aviation interests on November 10, 2018, twelve days after the Lion Air crash.<ref name=\"AvHerald\">{{cite web |last1=Hradecky |first1=Simon |title=Crash: Lion B38M near Jakarta on Oct 29th 2018, aircraft lost height and crashed into Java Sea, wrong AoA data |url=http://avherald.com/h?article=4bf90724/0009&opt=0 |website=The Aviation Herald |accessdate=2 March 2020 |date=January 14, 2019}}</ref> Boeing had also been aware of other software issues that suppressed a crucial AoA disagree message. With no knowledge of MCAS and its behavior, the pilots of the Lion Air flight, the first to crash, were at a disadvantage when attempting to respond to the system's erroneous activation. Procedures emphasized by Boeing and the [[U.S. Federal Aviation Administration|FAA]] did not prevent the later Ethiopian Airlines crash, which led to {{No selflink|Boeing 737 MAX groundings|the worldwide grounding}} of the airliner. \n\nMCAS was first deployed on the Boeing [[KC-46]] Air Force tanker, where it \"similarly moves the stabilizer in a wind-up turn\".<ref name=\"seattletimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/times-watchdog/the-inside-story-of-mcas-how-boeings-737-max-system-gained-power-and-lost-safeguards/|title=The inside story of MCAS: How Boeing's 737 MAX system gained power and lost safeguards|date=2019-06-22|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref> Unlike the 737 MAX, however, MCAS could be overridden on the KC-46 by pulling back on its control column. The Wall Street Journal reported in May 2019 that Boeing failed to share information about that issue for \"about a year\" before the Lion Air crash in Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Wall Street Journal |page=A1 | title=Boeing Knew of Problem for a Year |author1=Andy Pasztor |author2= Andrew Tangel |author3=Alison Sider |date=May 6, 2019}}</ref>\n<section end=\"summary\" />\n\n== Introduction ==\n<!-- Affected four system elements: 1. Avionics (Computer displays, AoA alert & indicator, etc.), 2. Flight controls (MCAS, horizontal stabilizer, manual trim, etc.), 3. Lightning protections (foil) and 4. Electrical systems (wiring bundles) --><!-- This shows safety measure related to MCAS/AoA by Boeing/FAA after the first crash but was not enough to avoid the second crash -->\n\n[[File:Adjustable stabilizer.svg|thumb|The MAX uses an adjustable stabilizer, moved by a jackscrew, to provide the required pitch trim forces. Generic stabilizer illustrated.]]\n\nThe {{No selflink|Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System}} (MCAS) [[flight control law]] was implemented on the 737 MAX to mitigate the aircraft's tendency to [[Aircraft principal axes|pitch up]] because of the aerodynamic effect of its larger, heavier, and more powerful CFM [[CFM International LEAP|LEAP-1B engines]] and nacelles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2018/11/14/boeings-automatic-trim-for-the-737-max-was-not-disclosed-to-the-pilots/|title=Boeing's automatic trim for the 737 MAX was not disclosed to the Pilots|date=2018-11-14|website=Leeham News and Analysis}}</ref> The stated goal of MCAS, according to Boeing, was to provide consistent aircraft handling characteristics at elevated angles of attack in certain unusual flight conditions only and hence make the 737 MAX perform similarly to its immediate predecessor, the [[737NG]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/737-max-updates/737-max-answers//|title=Your 737 MAX Questions. Answered: 5. What is MCAS?|publisher=Boeing}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n |align = center\n |width = \n |image1 = Boeing 737-200 (Brasilia Air Base) JT8D.jpg\n |width1 = 180\n |caption1 = 737-200 JT8D engine with original cowling design\n |image2 = CFM-56 Lauda 737.jpg\n |width2 = 177\n |caption2 = 737-800 (Next Generation) CFM56 engine with ovoid inlet\n |image3 = Boeing 737-9 MAX CFM LEAP-1B PAS.jpg\n |width3 = 184\n |caption3 = 737 MAX 9 CFM LEAP-1B engine with 787-derived engine chevrons\n}}\n\n==== MCAS's role in the accidents ====\n[[File:Lion Air Flight 610.svg|thumb|The tracking data of Lion Air Flight 610 from [[Flightradar24]]]] [[File:Vertical airspeeds of Boeing Max 737s in 2018-2019 crashes.jpg|alt=Vertical airspeeds of Boeing Max 737s in 2018-2019 crashes|thumb|The vertical airspeeds of the Boeing 737 MAX 8s involved in the JT 610 and ET 302 crashes]]\nInvestigators determined that MCAS was triggered by falsely high [[angle of attack]] (AoA) inputs, as if the plane had [[Aircraft principal axes|pitched]] up excessively. On both flights, shortly after takeoff, MCAS repeatedly actuated the [[horizontal stabilizer]] [[Trim tab|trim]] motor to push down the airplane nose.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-software-updates.page|title=737 MAX software update|publisher=Boeing}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saemobilus.sae.org/automated-connected/news/2019/04/boeing-flies-a-737-max-7-with-mcas-software-update|title=Boeing flies first 737 MAX 7 with MCAS software update|website=saemobilus.sae.org|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intelligent-aerospace.com/home/article/16537707/the-boeing-737-max-is-the-problem-with-the-plane-or-the-pilots|title=The Boeing 737 MAX: Is the problem with the plane or the pilots?|date=2019-03-12|website=Intelligent Aerospace|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://graphics.reuters.com/ETHIOPIA-AIRLINE-CONTROLS/0100916V1NZ/index.html|title=Change to 737 MAX controls may have imperiled planes|publisher=Reuters|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> [[Tracking (commercial airline flight)|Satellite data]] for the flights, [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302|ET 302]] and [[Lion Air Flight 610|JT 610]], showed that the planes struggled to gain altitude.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-13/doomed-737-caught-on-satellite-data-that-could-aid-investigation|title=Clue Linking Mysterious Boeing 737 Max Disasters Came From Space|last1=Levin|first1=Alan|website=Bloomberg News|access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref> Pilots reported difficulty controlling the airplane and asked to return to the airport.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/canada-grounds-boeing-737-max-8-leaving-us-as-last-major-user-of-plane/2019/03/13/25ac2414-459d-11e9-90f0-0ccfeec87a61_story.html |title=FAA's emergency order grounding Boeing jets came after the agency identified similarities between crashes in Ethiopia, Indonesia |first1=Luz |last1=Lazo |first2=Michael |last2=Laris |first3=Lori |last3=Aratani |first4=Damian |last4=Paletta |date=March 13, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/20/world/asia/lion-air-crash-boeing.html |title=Confusion, Then Prayer, in Cockpit of Doomed Lion Air Jet |last1=Beech |first1=Hannah |date=March 20, 2019 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 21, 2019 |last2=Suhartono |first2=Muktita}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2019, after China had grounded the aircraft,<ref name=\"sea-tim-03-17-19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/failed-certification-faa-missed-safety-issues-in-the-737-max-system-implicated-in-the-lion-air-crash/|title=Flawed analysis, failed oversight: How Boeing, FAA certified the suspect 737 MAX flight control system|last1=Gates|first1=Dominic|date=March 18, 2019|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Boeing published some details of new system requirements for the MCAS software and for the cockpit displays, which it began implementing in the wake of the prior accident five months earlier:<ref name=\":12\" />\n* If the two AOA sensors disagree with the flaps retracted, MCAS will not activate and an indicator will alert the pilots.\n* If MCAS is activated in non-normal conditions, it will only \"provide one input for each elevated AOA event.\"\n* Flight crew will be able to counteract MCAS by pulling back on the column.\n\nOn March 27, [[Daniel Elwell]], the acting administrator of the FAA, testified before the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation, saying that on January 21, \"Boeing submitted a proposed MCAS software enhancement to the FAA for certification. ... the FAA has tested this enhancement to the 737 MAX flight control system in both the simulator and the aircraft. The testing, which was conducted by FAA flight test engineers and flight test pilots, included aerodynamic stall situations and recovery procedures.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.transportation.gov/content/state-airline-safety-federal-oversight-commercial-aviation|title=The State of Airline Safety: Federal Oversight of Commercial Aviation|date=March 27, 2019|publisher=U.S. [[Department of Transportation]] (DOT)|access-date=July 27, 2019|quote=On January 21, 2019, Boeing submitted a proposed MCAS software enhancement to the FAA for certification. To date, the FAA has tested this enhancement to the 737 MAX flight control system in both the simulator and the aircraft. The testing, which was conducted by FAA flight test engineers and flight test pilots, included aerodynamic stall situations and recovery procedures.  The FAA's ongoing review of this software installation and training is an agency priority, as will be the roll-out of any software, training, or other measures to operators of the 737 MAX.}}</ref> After a series of delays, the updated MCAS software was released to the FAA in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeings-software-fix-for-737-max-still-weeks-away-from-delivery-to-faa/|title=Boeing's software fix for 737 MAX still weeks away from delivery to FAA|date=2019-04-01|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-04-02|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/03/19/boeing_repeats_737_max_software_update_promises/|title=Boeing big cheese repeats pledge of 737 Max software updates following fatal crashes|last=Corfield|first=Gareth|date=March 19, 2019|work=[[The Register]]|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> On May 16, Boeing announced that the completed software update was awaiting approval from the FAA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/737-max-boeing-software-fix/index.html|title=Boeing says it has completed 737 Max software fix|last=Rappard|first=Anna-Maja|last2=Wallace|first2=Gregory|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/05/16/boeing-says-max-update-held-up-by-faa-questions/|title=Boeing says 737 Max update is being held up by FAA questions|last=MacMillan|first=Douglas|date=May 16, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref> The flight software underwent 360 hours of testing on 207 flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/16/boeing-says-it-has-completed-the-development-of-updated-software-for-the-737-max.html|title=Boeing says it has completed a software update for 737 Max anti-stall system linked to fatal crashes|last=Josephs|first=Leslie|date=2019-05-16|publisher=CNBC|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> Boeing also updated existing crew procedures.<ref name=\":12\" /> The implementation of MCAS has been found to disrupt autopilot operations.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20190705\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-05/europe-sets-out-demands-for-boeing-before-max-can-fly-again|title=Boeing 737 Max's Autopilot Has Problem, European Regulators Find|date=2019-07-05|access-date=2019-07-06|publisher=Bloomberg News}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2019 Boeing publicly acknowledged that MCAS played a role in both accidents.<ref name=\"WashPost4apr2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/04/04/boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-apologizes-lives-lost-ethiopian-indonesian-plane-crashes/|title=Boeing CEO apologizes for lives lost and acknowledges role of company's flight-control system in two crashes|last1=Gregg|first1=Aaron|date=April 4, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Purpose of MCAS and the stabilizer trim system  ====\n<!-- MCAS description (what MCAS is and is not) -->\nThe FAA and Boeing both refuted media reports describing MCAS as an [[Stall (fluid dynamics)|anti-stall]] system, which Boeing asserted it is distinctly not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/faa-hearing-today-live-stream-updates-boeing-737-max-8-mcas-senate-commerce-committee-2019-03-27/|title=Congress holds fiery hearings on Boeing 737 Max 8 approval|website=[[CBS News]]|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeing-737-max-mcas-explained|title=The Boeing 737 MAX MCAS Explained|date=March 20, 2019|work=[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]]|first1=Sean |last1=Broderick |first2=Guy |last2=Norris |first3=Graham |last3=Warwick }}</ref><ref name=\"tac\">{{cite news|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/what-is-the-boeing-737-max-maneuvering-characteristics-augmentation-system-mcas-jt610/|title=What is the Boeing 737 Max Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System|last1=Ostrower|first1=Jon|date=November 13, 2018|access-date=March 14, 2019|website=The Air Current}}</ref> The aircraft had to perform well in a low-speed stall test.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/14/25.203 |title=14 CFR \u00a7 25.203 - Stall characteristics. |website=LII / Legal Information Institute |access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> The {{Pslink|Joint Authorities Technical Review}} \"considers that the STS/MCAS and elevator feel shift (EFS) functions could be considered as stall identification systems or stall protection systems, depending on the natural (unaugmented) stall characteristics of the aircraft\".\n\nThe JATR said, \"MCAS used the stabilizer to change the column force feel, not trim the aircraft. This is a case of using the control surface in a new way that the regulations never accounted for and should have required an issue paper for further analysis by the FAA. If the FAA technical staff had been fully aware of the details of the MCAS function, the JATR team believes the agency likely would have required an issue paper for using the stabilizer in a way that it had not previously been used; this [might have] identified the potential for the stabilizer to overpower the elevator.\"<ref name=\"Obs\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/media/attachments/Final_JATR_Submittal_to_FAA_Oct_2019.pdf|title=Boeing 737 MAX Flight Control System&nbsp;: Observations, Findings, and Recommendations|last=Hart|publisher=FAA|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Angle attack sensor hg.jpg|thumb|an [[angle of attack]] (AOA) sensor]]\n\n=== Background ===\n<!-- what is it? -->\nThe Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System (MCAS) is a [[Flight control modes|flight control law]]<ref name=\"737 MAX SOFTWARE UPDATE\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-software-updates.page#/overview|title=737 MAX SOFTWARE UPDATE|publisher=Boeing}}</ref> built into the [[Boeing 737 MAX]]'s flight control computer, designed to help the aircraft emulate the handling characteristics of the earlier [[Boeing 737 Next Generation]]. According to an international Civil Aviation Authorities team review (JATR) commissioned by the FAA, MCAS may be a stall identification or protection system, depending on the natural (unaugmented) stall characteristics of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Obs\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/?newsId=93206|title=FAA Updates on Boeing 737 MAX|website=www.faa.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Boeing considered MCAS part of the flight control system, and elected to not describe it in the flight manual or in training materials, based on the fundamental design philosophy of retaining commonality with the [[737NG]]. Minimizing the functional differences between the Boeing 737 MAX and Next Generation aircraft variants allowed both variants to share the same [[type rating]]. Thus, airlines can save money by employing and training one pool of pilots to fly both variants of the Boeing 737 interchangeably.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeing-737-max-mcas-explained|title=The Boeing 737 MAX MCAS Explained|last=Warwick|first=Graham|date=Mar 20, 2019|website=Aviation Week|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04|last4=Week}}</ref>\n\nWhen activated, MCAS directly engages the [[Stabilizer (aeronautics)|horizontal stabilizer]], thus is distinct from an anti-stall device, such as [[stick pusher]], which physically moves the pilot's control column forward and engages the airplane's [[Elevator (aeronautics)|elevators]] when the airplane is approaching a stall.\n\nBoeing's former CEO [[Dennis Muilenburg]] said \"[MCAS] has been reported or described as an anti-stall system, which it is not. It's a system that's designed to provide handling qualities for the pilot that meet pilot preferences.\"<ref name=\"BusinessInsider29apr2019\" />\n\n<!-- why? -->The 737 MAX's larger [[CFM LEAP|CFM LEAP-1B]] engines are fitted further forward and higher up than in previous models. The aerodynamic effect of its [[nacelle]]s contributes to the aircraft's tendency to [[Aircraft principal axes|pitch up]] at high [[angle of attack|angles of attack]] (AOA). The MCAS is intended to compensate in such cases, modeling the pitching behavior of previous models, and meet a certain certification requirement,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/14/25.203|title=14 CFR \u00a7 25.203 - Stall characteristics.|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> in order to enhance handling characteristics and thus minimizing the need for significant pilot retraining.<ref name=\"TAC13nov2018\">{{cite news|last1=Ostrower|first1=Jon|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/what-is-the-boeing-737-max-maneuvering-characteristics-augmentation-system-mcas-jt610/|title=What is the Boeing 737 Max Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System|date=November 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2019|website=The Air Current}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bazley |first1=Tarek |title=Control system under scrutiny after Ethiopian Airlines crash |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/control-system-scrutiny-ethiopian-airlines-crash-190311094532350.html |website=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=March 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessInsider29apr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Zhang |first1=Benjamin |title=Boeing's CEO explains why the company didn't tell 737 Max pilots about the software system that contributed to 2 fatal crashes |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/boeings-ceo-on-why-737-max-pilots-not-told-of-mcas-2019-4 |work=Business Insider |date=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe software code for the MCAS function and the computer for executing the software are built to Boeing's specifications by [[Collins Aerospace|Collins Aerospace, formerly Rockwell Collins]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/boeings-737-max-design-contains-fingerprints-of-hundreds-of-suppliers/2019/04/05/44f22024-57ab-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|title=Boeing's 737 Max design contains fingerprints of hundreds of suppliers|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boeing 737-524, Transaero Airlines AN2037840 (stab trim).jpg|thumb|upright|The trim wheel and cutoff switches in a previous generation cockpit]]\n\nAs an automated corrective measure, the MCAS was given full authority to bring the aircraft nose down, and could not be overridden by pilot resistance against the control wheel as on previous versions of the 737.<ref name=\"sullyTestimony\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sullysullenberger.com/my-testimony-today-before-the-house-subcommittee-on-aviation/|title=My Testimony Today Before the House Subcommittee on Aviation|date=2019-06-19|website=Sully Sullenberger|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref> Following the Lion Air accident, Boeing issued an Operations Manual Bulletin (OMB)<ref>{{cite web |title=Boeing Statement on Operations Manual Bulletin |url=https://boeing.mediaroom.com/news-releases-statements?item=130327 |publisher=Boeing |accessdate=2 July 2019 |date=November 6, 2018}}</ref> on November 6, 2019 to  outline the many indications and effects resulting from erroneous AOA data and provided instructions to turn off the motorized trim system for the remainder of the flight, and trim manually instead. Until Boeing supplemented the manuals<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyingmag.com/faa-emergency-airworthiness-directive-boeing-737-max-8/|title=FAA Issues Emergency AD Against Boeing 737 Max 8|website=Flying|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> and training, pilots were unaware of the existence of MCAS due to its omission from the crew manual and no coverage in training.<ref name=\"sullyTestimony\"/>  Boeing first publicly named and revealed the existence of MCAS on the 737 MAX in a message to airline operators and other aviation interests on November 10, 2018, twelve days after the Lion Air crash.<ref name=\"AvHerald\"/>\n\n=== Inception ===\nThe MCAS design parameters originally envisioned automated corrective actions to be taken in cases of high AoA and [[G-force]]s beyond normal flight conditions. [[Test pilot]]s routinely push aircraft to such extremes, as the FAA requires airplanes to perform as expected. Before the MCAS, test pilot Ray Craig determined the plane did not fly smoothly, in part due to the larger engines. Craig would have preferred an [[Aerodynamics|aerodynamic]] solution, but Boeing decided to implement a control law in software.\n\nAccording to a news report from the Wall Street Journal, engineers who had worked on the KC-46A Pegasus tanker, which includes an MCAS function, suggested MCAS to the design team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/before-737-max-boeings-flight-control-system-included-key-safeguards-11569754800|title=WSJ News Exclusive {{!}} Before 737 MAX, Boeing\u2019s Flight-Control System Included Key Safeguards|last=Tangel|first=Alison Sider and Andrew|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nWith the MCAS implemented, new test pilot Ed Wilson said the \"MAX wasn\u2019t handling well when nearing stalls at low speeds\u201d and recommended MCAS to apply across a broader range of flight conditions. This required the MCAS to function under normal G-forces and, at stalling speeds, deflect the vertical trim more rapidly and to a greater extent\u2014but now it reads a single AoA sensor.\n\nThe FAA did not conduct a safety analysis on the changes. It had already approved the previous version of MCAS, and the agency's rules did not require it to take a second look because the changes did not affect how the plane operated in extreme situations.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/01/business/boeing-737-max-crash.html|title=Boeing Built Deadly Assumptions Into 737 Max, Blind to a Late Design Change|last=Nicas|first=Jack|date=2019-06-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-07|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Gelles|first3=David|last4=Glanz|first4=James}}</ref>\n\n=== Safety engineering and human factors ===\nAs with any other equipment on board an aircraft, the FAA approves a functional \"design assurance level\"  corresponding to the consequences of a failure, using the [[SAE International]] standards [[ARP4754]] and [[ARP4761|ARP4761.]] MCAS was designated a \"hazardous failure\" system. This classification corresponds to failures causing \"a large reduction in safety margins\" or \"serious or fatal injury to a relatively small number of the occupants\", but nothing \"catastrophic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/2/18518176/boeing-737-max-crash-problems-human-error-mcas-faa|title=The many human errors that brought down the Boeing 737 Max|last=Campbell|first=Darryl|date=2019-05-02|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\nThe MCAS was designed with the assumption, approved by FAA, that pilots would react to an unexpected activation within three seconds.<ref name=\"seattletimes.com\"/>\n\n=== MCAS on the Boeing KC-46 ===\nMCAS exists in a different form on the [[Boeing KC-46 Pegasus]], an [[aerial refueling]] tanker that is fundamentally a [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-2C]]. The system takes input on dual redundant angle of attack sensors; it will disengage with stick input by the pilot. The Air Force stated that \"The KC-46 has protections that ensure pilot manual inputs have override priority\" and that it \"does not fly the models of aircraft involved in the recent accidents\" and that it is \"reviewing our procedures and training as part of our normal and ongoing review process.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.airforcemag.com/Features/Pages/2019/March%202019/USAF-Reviewing-Training-After-MAX-8-Crashes-KC-46-Uses-Similar-MCAS-System.aspx|title=USAF Reviewing Training After MAX 8 Crashes; KC-46 Uses Similar MCAS|website=www.airforcemag.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323043919/http://www.airforcemag.com/Features/Pages/2019/March%25202019/USAF-Reviewing-Training-After-MAX-8-Crashes-KC-46-Uses-Similar-MCAS-System.aspx|archive-date=2019-03-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== MCAS technology readiness ==\nBoeing presented MCAS to the FAA as being existing technology, avoiding  deeper scrutiny. The U.S. House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee provided all 43 Boeing's presentation slides in the document titled \"MCAS Development and Certification Overview.\" at the request of the Seattle Times, which noted that MCAS was not evaluated as an individual system that was \"new/novel on the MAX.\" The FAA is required to be closely involved in the testing and certification of any new and novel features on an aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/after-lion-air-crash-boeing-doubled-down-on-faulty-737-max-assumptions/|title=After Lion Air crash, Boeing doubled down on faulty 737 MAX assumptions|date=2019-11-08|website=The Seattle Times|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Aerospace reporter Dominic Gates summarized: \"The justification given was a doubtful comparison with the 767 tanker\".\n\nJust before entering certification, the functional requirements for MCAS were still changing. Boeing modified MCAS so that it intervened more strongly and at lower airspeeds than originally planned. \"Inadvertently, the door was now opened to serious system misbehavior during the busy and stressful moments right after takeoff\", said Jenkins of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/boeing-vs-technological-chaos-11572998029|title=Boeing vs. Technological Chaos|last=Jenkins|first=Holman W. jr.|date=2019-11-05|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\nThe JATR found the technology unprecedented: \"If the FAA technical staff had been fully aware of the details of the MCAS function, the JATR team believes the agency likely would have required an issue paper for using the stabilizer in a way that it had not previously been used. MCAS used the stabilizer to change the column force feel, not trim the aircraft. This is a case of using the control surface in a new way that the regulations never accounted for and should have required an issue paper for further analysis by the FAA. If an issue paper had been required, the JATR team believes it likely would have identified the potential for the stabilizer to overpower the elevator.\"<ref name=\"Obs\" />\n\n== Scrutiny ==\n[[File:Lion Air Flight 610.svg|thumb|Altitude and speed of Lion Air Flight 610]]\nThe MCAS has been under scrutiny following the fatal crashes of [[Lion Air Flight 610]] and [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]] soon after takeoff. The Boeing 737 MAX global fleet has been [[Boeing 737 MAX groundings|grounded]] by all airlines and operators, and a number of functional issues have been raised.<ref name=\"Gates\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/failed-certification-faa-missed-safety-issues-in-the-737-max-system-implicated-in-the-lion-air-crash/ |title=Flawed analysis, failed oversight: How Boeing and FAA certified the suspect 737 MAX flight control system|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|first= Dominic |last= Gates|date=March 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/04/05/bjorns-corner-et302-crash-report-the-first-analysis/|title=Bjorn's Corner: ET302 crash report, the first analysis|last=Fehrm|first=Bjorn|date=2019-04-05|work=Leeham News and Analysis}}</ref><ref name=\"Gates_20191029\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-ceo-must-have-answers-about-the-737-max-as-he-faces-congressional-scrutiny-this-week/ |title=Live coverage: Boeing CEO Dennis Muilenburg testifies to Congress about 737 MAX |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|first= Dominic |last= Gates|date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe use of a single AOA sensor at any one time creates a [[single point of failure]] and leads to the possibility that a single malfunctioning sensor could produce erroneous data, cause the MCAS system to pitch the nose downward and force the aircraft into a dive.<ref name=\"https\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/a-lack-of-redundancies-on-737-max-system-has-baffled-even-those-who-worked-on-the-jet/|title=Lack of redundancies on Boeing 737 MAX system baffles some involved in developing the jet|last1=Baker|first1=Mike|last2=Gates|first2=Dominic|date=March 26, 2019|website=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref name=TAC13nov2018/><!--ref name=IEEE18apr2019/-->\n\nThe MCAS deflects the horizontal stabilizer four times farther than was stated in the initial safety analysis document.<ref name=\"Gates\"/> Due to the amount of trim the system applies to the horizontal stabilizer, aerodynamic forces resist pilot control effort to raise the nose. As long as the faulty AOA readings persist, a human pilot \"can quickly become exhausted trying to pull the column back\".<ref name=\"IEEE18apr2019\">{{cite news|last1=Travis|first1=Gregory|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424114042/https://spectrum.ieee.org/aerospace/aviation/how-the-boeing-737-max-disaster-looks-to-a-software-developer|title=How the Boeing 737 Max Disaster Looks to a Software Developer|date=April 18, 2019|work=IEEE Spectrum}}</ref> In addition, switches for the horizontal stabilizer trim assist now serve a shared purpose of turning off the MCAS. In simulator sessions, pilots were stunned by the substantial effort needed to manually crank the trim wheel out of its nose down setting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/04/03/et302-used-the-cut-out-switches-to-stop-mcas/|title=ET302 used the Cut-Out switches to stop MCAS|last=Bjorn|first=Fehrm|date=2019-04-03|website=Leeham News and Analysis}}</ref><ref name=\"Mike Baker and Dominic Gates\">{{Cite news|author=Mike Baker and Dominic Gates|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-altered-key-switches-in-737-max-cockpit-limiting-ability-to-shut-off-mcas/|title=Boeing altered key switches in 737 MAX cockpit, limiting ability to shut off MCAS|date=May 10, 2019|newspaper=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref name=AvWeek10may2019>{{cite news |url= https://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/ethiopian-max-crash-simulator-scenario-stuns-pilots |title= Ethiopian MAX Crash Simulator Scenario Stuns Pilots |date= May 10, 2019 |author= Sean Broderick |work= Aviation Week Network}}</ref>\n\nBoeing and the FAA decided that the AOA display and an AOA disagree light, which signals if the sensors give different readings, were not critical features for safe operation.<ref name=Reuters30nov2018>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-crash-boeing-aoa/optional-warning-light-could-have-aided-lion-air-engineers-before-crash-experts-idUSKCN1NZ0QL|title=Optional warning light could have aided Lion Air engineers before crash: experts|first1=Jamie|last1=Freed|first2=Eric |last2=Johnson|date=November 30, 2018|agency=Reuters}}</ref> Boeing charged extra for the addition of the AoA indicator to the primary display.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Newburger |first1=Emma |title=Crashed jets reportedly lacked key safety features because Boeing charged extra for them |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/21/crashed-boeing-jets-lacked-key-safety-features-that-were-add-ons.html |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |publisher=CNBC |date=March 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=NYtimes21mar2019>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/business/boeing-safety-features-charge.html |title= Doomed Boeing Jets Lacked 2 Safety Features That Company Sold Only as Extras |first1= Hiroko |last1= Tabucho |first2= David |last2= Gelles |date= March 21, 2019 |accessdate= March 21, 2019 |work= [[The New York Times]] }}</ref> In November 2017, Boeing engineers discovered that the standard AoA disagree light cannot independently function without the optional AoA indicator software, affecting 80% of the global fleet which had not ordered the option.<ref name=\"Gelles\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/05/business/boeing-737-max-warning-light.html|title=Boeing Believed a 737 Max Warning Light Was Standard. It Wasn't.|last=Gelles|first=David|date=2019-05-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-11|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/faa-considered-grounding-boeing-737-max-planes-last-180808293.html|title=FAA considered grounding some Boeing 737 Max planes last year: source|website=news.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref> The software remedy was scheduled to coincide with the roll out of the elongated [[737 MAX 10]] in 2020, only to be accelerated by the [[Lion Air Flight 610|Lion Air accident]]. Furthermore, the problem had not been disclosed to the FAA until 13 months after the fact. Although it is unclear whether the indicator could have changed the  outcome for the ill-fated flights, American Airlines said the disagree indicator provided the assurance in continued operations of the airplane. \"As it turned out, that wasn't true.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/024ba22014d647a481d52e52ab8dde61|title=Boeing wanted to wait 3 years to fix safety alert on 737 Max|last=Koenig|first=David|last2=Krisher|first2=Tom|date=2019-06-07|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\nBoeing CEO [[Dennis Muilenburg]] has stated that there was \"no surprise, or gap, or unknown here or something that somehow slipped through a certification process.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bizjournals.com/wichita/news/2019/04/24/boeing-ceo-nothing-slipped-through-in-original-737.html |title= Boeing CEO: Nothing slipped through in original 737 MAX certification |author= Daniel McCoy |work= Wichita Business Journal |date= Apr 24, 2019}}</ref> On April 29, 2019 he stated the design of the aircraft was not flawed and reiterated that it was designed per Boeing's standards.<ref name=SeattleTimes29apr2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/facing-sharp-questions-boeing-ceo-refuses-to-admit-flaws-in-737-max-design/ |title= Facing sharp questions, Boeing CEO refuses to admit flaws in 737 MAX design |author= Dominic Gates |work= Seattle Times |date= Apr 29, 2019}}</ref> In a May 29 interview with CBS, Boeing admitted that it had botched the software implementation and lamented the poor communications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-says-he-would-put-his-family-737-max-without-any-hesitation-exclusive-2019-05-29/|title=Boeing CEO says he would put his family in a 737 Max \"without any hesitation\"|last=May 29|first=CBS News|last2=2019|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12|last3=Pm|first3=6:50}}</ref>\n\nOn September 26, the [[National Transportation Safety Board]] criticized Boeing\u2019s inadequate testing of the 737 MAX, and pointed out that Boeing made erroneous assumptions on pilots\u2019 response to alerts in 737 MAX, triggered by activation of MCAS due to a faulty signal from an angle-of-attack sensor.<ref name=\"ntsb20190926\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/26/business/boeing-737-max-ntsb-mcas.html|title=Boeing Underestimated Cockpit Chaos on 737 Max, N.T.S.B. Says|last=Kitroeff|first=Natalie|date=2019-09-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/ASR1901.pdf|title=Safety Recommendation Report: Assumptions Used in the Safety Assessment Process and the Effects of Multiple Alerts and Indications on Pilot Performance|last=|first=|date=19 September 2019|website=www.ntsb.gov|publisher=NTSB|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-26|layurl=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Pages/ASR1901.aspx}}</ref>\n\nThe Joint Authorities Technical Review (JATR), a team commissioned by the FAA for 737 MAX investigation, concluded that FAA failed to properly review MCAS. Boeing failed to provide adequate and updated technical information regarding the MCAS system to FAA during Boeing 737 Max certification process, and had not carried out a thorough verification by [[stress-testing]] of the MCAS system.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-boeing-airplane-faa-idUSKBN1WQ0H8|title=FAA failed to properly review 737 MAX jet anti-stall system: JATR findings|date=2019-10-11|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-10-11|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/11/business/boeing-737-max.html|title=Review of 737 Max Certification Finds Fault With Boeing and F.A.A.|last=Gelles|first=David|date=2019-10-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-11|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, Boeing turned over a discussion from 2016 between two employees which revealed prior issues with the MCAS system.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/text-messages-show-boeing-employees-knew-in-2016-of-problems-that-turned-deadly-on-the-737-max/2019/10/18/8578c990-f1ca-11e9-89eb-ec56cd414732_story.html|title=Messages show Boeing employees knew in 2016 of problems that turned deadly on the 737 Max|last=Laris|first=Michael|date=2019-10-18|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n=== NTSB === <!-- Boeing knowledge about MAX airworthiness design issues and its measure-->\n\nOn September 26, 2019, the NTSB released the results of its review of potential lapses in the design and approval of the 737 MAX.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/26/business/boeing-737-max-ntsb-mcas.html|title=Boeing Underestimated Cockpit Chaos on 737 Max, N.T.S.B. Says|last=Kitroeff|first=Natalie|date=2019-09-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-09-26|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":31\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/ASR1901.pdf|title=Safety Recommendation Report: Assumptions Used in the Safety Assessment Process and the Effects of Multiple Alerts and Indications on Pilot Performance|date=September 19, 2019|publisher=NTSB|access-date=2019-09-26|layurl=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Pages/ASR1901.aspx}}{{NTSB}}</ref>{{rp|page=1}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntsb.gov/news/press-releases/Pages/NR20190926.aspx|title=NTSB Issues 7 Safety Recommendations to FAA related to Ongoing Lion Air, Ethiopian Airlines Crash Investigations|website=NTSB|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> The NTSB report concludes that assumptions \"that Boeing used in its functional hazard assessment of uncommanded MCAS function for the 737 MAX did not adequately consider and account for the impact that multiple flight deck alerts and indications could have on pilots' responses to the hazard\". When Boeing induced a stabilizer trim input that simulated the stabilizer moving consistent with the MCAS function, \"... the specific failure modes that could lead to unintended MCAS activation (such as an erroneous high AOA input to the MCAS) were not simulated as part of these functional hazard assessment validation tests. As a result, additional flight deck effects (such as IAS DISAGREE and ALT DISAGREE alerts and stick shaker activation) resulting from the same underlying failure (for example, erroneous AOA) were not simulated and were not in the stabilizer trim safety assessment report reviewed by the NTSB.\"<ref name=\":31\" /><ref name=\":31\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/19781330-e5cd-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59|title=Boeing report highlights human factors no company should ignore|last=Hill|first=Andrew|date=October 6, 2019|work=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe NTSB questioned the long-held industry and FAA practice of assuming the nearly instantaneous responses of highly trained test pilots as opposed to pilots of all levels of experience to verify [[human factors]] in aircraft safety.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/plane-tests-must-use-average-pilots-ntsb-says-after-737-max-crashes-11569506401|title=Plane Tests Must Use Average Pilots, NTSB Says After 737 MAX Crashes|last=Pasztor|first=Andy|date=September 26, 2019|access-date=2019-09-27|author-link=Andy Pasztor|url-access=subscription|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> The NTSB expressed concerns that the process used to evaluate the original design needs improvement because that process is still in use to certify current and future aircraft and system designs. The FAA could for example randomly sample pools from the worldwide pilot community to get a more representative assessment of cockpit situations.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5687473/boeing-737-alarm-system/|title=Boeing Failed to Predict That Slew of 737 Max Warning Alarms Would Confuse Pilots, Investigators Say|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== Supporting systems==\nThe updates proposed by Boeing focus mostly on MCAS software.<ref name=\"737 MAX SOFTWARE UPDATE\"/> In particular, there have been no public statements regarding reverting the functionality of the stabilizer trim cutout switches to pre-MAX configuration. A veteran software engineer and experienced pilot suggested that software changes may not be enough to counter the 737 MAX's engine placement.<ref name=EETimes27mar2019>{{cite news |url= https://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1334482 |title= Software Won't Fix Boeing's 'Faulty' Airframe |work= [[EE Times]] |author= George Leopold |date= March 27, 2019 }}</ref> Seattle Times notes that while the new software fix Boeing has proposed \"will likely prevent this situation recurring, if the preliminary investigation confirms that the Ethiopian pilots did cut off the automatic flight-control system, this is still a nightmarish outcome for Boeing and the FAA. It would suggest the emergency procedure laid out by Boeing and passed along by the FAA after the Lion Air crash is wholly inadequate and failed the Ethiopian flight crew.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeings-emergency-procedure-for-737-max-may-have-failed-on-ethiopian-flight/|title=Why Boeing's emergency directions may have failed to save 737 MAX|date=2019-04-03|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Jim Marko, a manager of aircraft integration and safety assessment at [[Transport Canada]] aviation regulator's National Aircraft Certification Branch questioned the readiness of MCAS. Because new problems kept emerging, he suggested to his peers at FAA, ANAC and EASA to consider the safety benefits of removing MCAS from the MAX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/transport-canada-safety-official-urges-removal-of-mcas-from-737-max/|title=Transport Canada safety official urges removal of MCAS from 737 Max|date=2019-11-23|website=The Air Current|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Angle of Attack (AoA) ===\nAs per Boeing technical description: \"the [[Angle of attack|Angle of Attack]] (AOA) is an aerodynamic parameter that is key to understanding the limits of airplane performance. Recent accidents and incidents have resulted in new flight crew training programs, which in turn have raised interest in AOA in commercial aviation. Awareness of AOA is vitally important as the airplane nears stall.\"<ref name=\"Boeing_AOA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_12/aoa.pdf|title=Angle of attack|year=2000|website=Aero magazine - Issue 12|publisher=Boeing|access-date= 2019-07-27| layurl=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_12/}}</ref> [[Chesley Sullenberger]] said AoA indicators might have helped in these two crashes. \"It is ironic that most modern aircraft measure (angle of attack) and that information is often used in many aircraft systems, but it is not displayed to pilots. Instead, pilots must infer (angle of attack) from other parameters, deducing it indirectly.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Did-Boeing-aviation-industry-heed-lessons-of-14369021.php|title=Did Boeing, aviation industry heed lessons of 2009 Air France crash?|last=Leinfelder|first=Andrea|date=2019-08-22|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> \n\n==== AoA sensors ====\nThough there are two sensors on the MAX only one of them is used at a time to trigger MCAS activation on the 737 MAX. Any fault in this sensor, perhaps due to physical damage,<ref name=\"sullysullenberger.com\"/> creates a [[single point of failure|single point failure]]: the flight control system lacks any basis for rejecting its input as faulty information.\n\nReports of a single point of failure were not always acknowledged by Boeing. Addressing American Airlines pilots, Boeing vice-president Mike Sinnett contradicted reports that the MCAS had a single-point failure, because the pilots themselves are the backup. Reporter Useem said in [[The Atlantic]] it was \"showing both a misunderstanding of the term and a sharp break from Boeing's long-standing practice of having multiple backups for every flight system\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/11/how-boeing-lost-its-bearings/602188/|title=The Long-Forgotten Flight That Sent Boeing Off Course|last=Useem|first=Jerry|date=2019-11-20|website=The Atlantic|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\nProblems with the AoA sensor had been reported in over 200 incident reports submitted to the FAA; however, Boeing did not flight test a scenario in which it malfunctioned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/30/politics/boeing-sensor-737-max-faa/index.html|title=Boeing relied on single sensor for 737 Max that had been flagged 216 times to FAA|author1=Curt Devine |author2=Drew Griffin|website=[[CNN]]|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nThe sensors themselves are under scrutiny. Sensors on the Lion air aircraft were supplied by United Technologies' Rosemount Aerospace.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/sensor-cited-as-potential-factor-in-boeing-crashes-draws-scrutiny/2019/03/17/5ecf0b0e-4682-11e9-aaf8-4512a6fe3439_story.html |title=Sensor cited as potential factor in Boeing crashes draws scrutiny|last=Frankel|first=Todd C.|date=2019-03-17|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the EASA said it prefers triple-redundant AoA sensors rather than the dual redundancy in Boeing's proposed upgrade to the MAX.<ref name=\":18\" /> Installation of a third sensor could be expensive and take a long time. The change, if mandated, could be extended to thousands of older model 737s in service around the world.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/european-regulator-plans-its-own-test-flights-of-boeing-737-max-in-sign-of-differences-with-faa/|title=European regulator plans its own test flights of Boeing 737 MAX in sign of rift with FAA|date=2019-09-10|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-09-11|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref>\n\nA former professor at [[Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University]], Andrew Kornecki, who is an expert in redundancy systems, said operating with one or two sensors \"would be fine if all the pilots were sufficiently trained in how to assess and handle the plane in the event of a problem\". But, he would much prefer building the plane with three sensors, as Airbus does.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/a-lack-of-redundancies-on-737-max-system-has-baffled-even-those-who-worked-on-the-jet/|title=Lack of redundancies on Boeing 737 MAX system baffles some involved in developing the jet|date=2019-03-26|first1=Mike |last1=Baker |first2=Dominic |last2=Gates|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n==== AoA Disagree alert ====\nIn November 2017, after several months of MAX deliveries, Boeing discovered that the <span style=\"font-variant: small-caps;\">''AoA Disagree''</span> message, which is indicative of potential sensor mismatch on the [[primary flight display]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/03/27/boeing-presents-mcas-fix-to-pilots-regulators-and-media/|title=Boeing presents MCAS fix to pilots, regulators and media|last=Fehrm|first=Bjorn|date=2019-03-27|website=Leeham News and Analysis|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> was unintentionally disabled.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nClint Balog, a professor at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University, said after the Lion Air crash: \"In retrospect, clearly it would have been wise to include the warning as standard equipment and fully inform and train operators on MCAS\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-crash-boeing-aoa-idUSKCN1NZ0QL|title=Optional warning light could have aided Lion Air engineers before crash: experts|date=2018-11-30|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> According to Bjorn Fehrm, Aeronautical and Economic Analyst at Leeham News and Analysis, \"A major contributor to the ultimate loss of JT610 is the missing AOA DISAGREE display on the pilots' displays.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/11/15/bjorns-corner-analysing-the-lion-air-jt610-crash-part-3/|title=Bjorn's Corner: Analysing the Lion Air JT610 crash, Part 3.|last=Fehrm|first=Bjorn|date=2019-11-15|website=Leeham News and Analysis|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nThe software depended on the presence of the visual indicator software, a paid option that was not selected most airlines. <ref name=\":53\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/18/the-case-against-boeing|title=The Case Against Boeing|last=MacGillis|first=Alec|date=2019-11-11|access-date=2019-11-11|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> For example, Air Canada, American Airlines and Westjet had purchased the disagree alert, while Air Canada and American Airlines also purchased, in addition, the [[#Visual AoA indicator|AoA value indicator]], and Lion Air had neither.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/amp/1.5065888|title=Air Canada says their 737 Max jets have all safety features Boeing sells as extras|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2019|work=CBC.ca|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Optional warning light could have aided Lion Air engineers before crash: experts|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-crash-boeing-aoa/optional-warning-light-could-have-aided-lion-air-engineers-before-crash-experts-idUSKCN1NZ0QL|date=2018-11-30|access-date=2019-11-13|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> Boeing had determined that the defect was not critical to aircraft safety or operation, and an internal [[Functional safety|safety review board]] (SRB) corroborated Boeing's prior assessment and its initial plan to update the aircraft in 2020. Boeing did not disclose the defect to the FAA until November 2018, in the wake of the Lion Air crash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-boeing-737-max-safety-alert-20190607-story.html|title=Boeing wanted to wait three years to fix safety alert on 737 Max|date=2019-06-07|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-08-03|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Boeing AOA Disagree Alert\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/05/business/boeing-737-max-warning-light.html|title=Boeing Believed a 737 Max Warning Light Was Standard. It Wasn't.|last=Gelles|first=David|date=2019-05-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-08-27|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/business/boeing-safety-features-charge.html|title=Doomed Boeing Jets Lacked 2 Safety Features That Company Sold Only as Extras|last=Tabuchi|first=Hiroko|date=2019-03-21|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-08-27|last2=Gelles|first2=David|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Consequently, Southwest had announced to pilots that its entire fleet of MAX 8 aircraft will receive the optional upgrades.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/southwest-airlines-is-adding-new-angle-of-attack-indicators-to-its-737-max-fleet/|title=Southwest is adding new Angle of Attack indicators to its 737 Max fleet|date=2018-11-30|website=The Air Current|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aviationtoday.com/2018/11/30/lion-air-report-analyzes-pilot-struggle-737-max-trim-system/|title=Lion Air Report Analyzes Pilot Struggle With 737 MAX Trim System|date=2018-11-30|website=Avionics|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> In March 2019, after the second accident of Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302, a Boeing representative told ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]'' magazine, \"Customers have been informed that AOA disagree alert will become a standard feature on the 737 Max. It can be retrofitted on previously delivered airplanes.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/minda-zetlin/boeing-safety-features-options-upgrades-angle-attack-disagree-light-mcas-lion-air-ethiopian.html|title=Boeing CEO Says Safety Is Highest Priority. The Company's Pricing Says Something Different|last=Zetlin|first=Minda|date=2019-03-24|website=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2019, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that Boeing had known of existing problems with the flight control system a year before the Lion Air accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/boeing-knew-about-safety-alert-problem-for-a-year-before-telling-faa-airlines-11557087129|title=Boeing Knew About Safety-Alert Problem for a Year Before Telling FAA, Airlines|last=Pasztor|first=Andy|date=May 5, 2019|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=December 24, 2019|last2=Tangel|first2=Andrew|last3=Sider|first3=Alison|author-link1=Andy Pasztor|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Boeing defended that \"Neither the angle of attack indicator nor the AoA Disagree alert are necessary for the safe operation of the airplane.\" Boeing recognized that the defective software was not implemented to their specifications as a \"standard, standalone feature.\" Boeing stated, \"...MAX production aircraft will have an activated and operable AOA Disagree alert and an optional angle of attack indicator. All customers with previously delivered MAX airplanes will have the ability to activate the AOA Disagree alert.\"<ref name=\"Boeing AOA Disagree Alert\" /> Boeing CEO Muilenburg said the company's communication about the alert \"was not consistent. And that's unacceptable.\"<ref name=\"voanews_20190616_warning\">{{cite news |url= https://www.voanews.com/usa/boeing-ceo-admits-mistake-handling-warning-system-problem |title= Boeing CEO Admits Mistake in Handling Warning-System Problem |agency= Associated Press |date= June 16, 2019 |via= [[Voice of America|VOA]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Boeing AOA Disagree Alert\">{{cite press release |url= https://boeing.mediaroom.com/news-releases-statements?item=130431 |title= Boeing Statement on AOA Disagree Alert |publisher= Boeing |date= 2019-05-05 |access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Visual AoA indicator ====\n[[File:Primary Flight Display of a Boeing 737-800.png|thumb|250px|upright|The [[primary flight display]] of a Boeing 737-800 aircraft with a functional [[angle of attack]] display on the upper right; the AoA Disagree alert would appear as a text message.]]\n\nBoeing published an article in ''Aero'' magazine about AoA systems, \"Operational use of Angle of Attack on modern commercial jet planes\": {{quote| The AOA indicator can be used to assist with unreliable airspeed indications as a result of blocked [[Pitot tube|pitot]] or static ports and may provide additional situation and configuration awareness to the flight crew.<ref name=\"Boeing_AOA\" />}}\n\nBoeing announced a change in policy in the Frequently Asked Questions in a ([[FAQ]]) about the MAX corrective work, \"With the software update, customers are not charged for the AOA disagree feature or their selection of the AOA indicator option.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-contacts.page|title=Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=Boeing: 737 MAX FAQ}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the NTSB issued Safety Recommendation A-96-094. <blockquote>TO THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION (FAA): ''Require that all transport-category aircraft present pilots with angle-of-attack info in a visual format, and that all air carriers train their pilots to use the info to obtain maximum possible airplane climb performance.''\n</blockquote>\n\nThe NTSB also stated about another accident in 1997, that \"a display of angle of attack on the flight deck would have maintained the flightcrew's awareness of the stall condition and it would have provided direct indication of the pitch attitudes required for recovery throughout the attempted stall recovery sequence.\" The NTSB also believed that the accident may have been prevented if a direct indication of AoA was presented to the flightcrew (NTSB, 1997).\"<ref>{{Cite report |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=20140011419 |title=Review of Research On Angle-of-Attack Indicator Effectiveness |last=Le Vie |first=Lisa R. |publisher=NASA [[Langley Research Center]] (LaRC) |date=August 1, 2014 |id=NASA/TM\u20132014-218514 |hdl=2060/20140011419}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|page=29}}\n\n=== Flight computer architecture ===\nIn early April 2019, Boeing reported a problem with software affecting flaps and other flight-control hardware, unrelated to MCAS; classified as critical to flight safety, the FAA has ordered Boeing to fix the problem correspondingly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/ethiopia-says-pilots-performed-boeings-recommendations-to-stop-doomed-aircraft-from-diving-urges-review-of-737-max-flight-control-system/2019/04/04/3a125942-4fec-11e9-bdb7-44f948cc0605_story.html|title=Additional software problem detected in Boeing 737 Max flight control system, officials say|first1=Aaron C. |last1=Davis |first2=Luz |last2=Lazo |first3=Paul |last3=Schemm |date=April 4, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\nIn October 2019, the EASA has suggested to conduct more testing on proposed revisions to flight-control computers due to its concerns about portions of proposed fixes to MCAS.<ref name=\"EASA on proposed fixes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/friction-between-u-s-european-regulators-could-delay-737-max-return-to-service-11570527001|title=Friction Between U.S., European Regulators Could Delay 737 MAX Return to Service |last1=Pasztor|first1=Andy|author-link1=Andy Pasztor|last2=Tangel|first2=Andrew|date=October 8, 2019|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=October 8, 2019|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\nThe necessary changes to improve redundancy between the two flight control computers have proved more complex and time-consuming than the fixes for the original MCAS issue, delaying any re-introduction to service beyond the date originally envisaged.<ref name=\"levin\"/>\n\n<!-- Flight computer start-up verification and self-diagnostics -->\nIn January 2020, new software issues were discovered, affecting monitoring of the flight computer start-up process and verifying readiness for flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashgear.com/boeing-finds-yet-another-737-max-software-issue-19607147/|title=Boeing finds yet another 737 MAX software issue|date=2020-01-19|website=SlashGear|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Microprocessor stress testing ====\nThe MAX systems are integrated in the \"e-cab\" test flight deck, a simulator built for developing the MAX.<ref name=\":51\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/news/the-e-cab-a-test-flight-deck.page|title=Boeing: The \"e-cab\" \u2013 a test flight deck|website=www.boeing.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=http://players.brightcove.net/800000612001/a7975ab0-d4c3-4514-a6c3-d7bfff0667c5_default/index.html?videoId=4637926975001|title=The \"e-cab\" \u2013 A Test Flight Deck|last=|first=|date=2015-11-30|website=players.brightcove.net|publisher=Boeing|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> In June 2019, \"in a special Boeing simulator that is designed for engineering reviews,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-boeing-737-max-new-glitch-20190627-story.html|title=Boeing needs up to three months to fix newly discovered 737 Max glitch|first=Alan |last=Levin |first2=Julie |last2=Johnsson |first3=Shaun |last3=Courtney|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> FAA pilots performed a [[Stress testing (software)|stress testing]] scenario{{snd}}an abnormal condition identified through [[Failure mode and effects analysis|FMEA]] after the MCAS update was implemented<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fehrm |first1=Bjorn |title=New pitch trim issue forces further changes to 737 MAX software |url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/06/28/bjorns-corner-new-pitch-trim-issue-forces-further-changes-to-737-max-software/ |work=Leeham News and Analysis |date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>{{snd}}for evaluating the effect of a fault in a microprocessor: as expected from the scenario, the horizontal stabilizer pointed the nose downward. Although the test pilot ultimately recovered control, the system was slow to respond to the proper runaway stabilizer checklist steps. Boeing initially classified this as a \"major\" hazard, and the FAA upgraded it to a much more severe \"catastrophic\" rating. Boeing stated that the issue can be fixed in software.<ref name=\"Boeing 737 MAX software\">{{cite press release|url=https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2019-06-26-Boeing-Statement-on-737-MAX-software|title=Boeing Statement on 737 MAX software|publisher=Boeing|date=June 26, 2019|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> The software change will not be ready for evaluation until at least September 2019.<ref name=\"aircurrent20190627\">{{cite news |last1=Ostrower |first1=Jon |title=FAA and Boeing initially disagreed on severity of \"catastrophic\" 737 Max software glitch |url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/faa-and-boeing-initially-disagreed-on-severity-of-catastrophic-737-max-software-glitch/ |work=The Air Current |date=June 27, 2019}}</ref> EASA director Patrick Ky said that retrofitting additional hardware is an option to be considered.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20190705\" />\n\nEarly news reports were inaccurate in attributing the problem to an [[Intel 80286|80286]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Allard |first1=Andr\u00e9 |title=MAX's computer has reached its limit |url=https://www.wingsoverquebec.com/?p=8649 |work=Wings Over Qu\u00e9bec |date=July 3, 2019 }}</ref> microprocessor overwhelmed with data. The test scenario simulated an event toggling five bits in the flight control computer. The bits represent status flags such as whether MCAS is active, or whether the tail trim motor is energized. Engineers were able to simulate [[single event upset]]s and artificially induce MCAS activation by manipulating these signals. Such a fault occurs when memory bits change from 0 to 1 or vice versa, which is something that can be caused by cosmic rays striking the microprocessor.<ref name=\"Seattle Times 20190801\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/newly-stringent-faa-tests-spur-a-fundamental-software-redesign-of-737-max-flight-controls/|title=Newly stringent FAA tests spur a fundamental software redesign of Boeing's 737 MAX flight controls|date=2019-08-01|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-08-02|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref>\n\nThe failure scenario was known before the MAX entered service in 2017: it had been assessed in a safety analysis when the plane was certified. Boeing had concluded that pilots could perform a procedure to shut off the motor driving the stabilizer to overcome the nose-down movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-27/latest-737-max-fault-that-alarmed-test-pilots-rooted-in-software|title=Latest 737 Max Fault That Alarmed Test Pilots Rooted in Software|publisher=Bloomberg News}}</ref> The scenario also affects [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|737NG]] aircraft, though it presents less risk than on the MAX. On the NG, moving the [[Yoke (aeronautics)|yoke]] counters any uncommanded stabilizer input, but this function is bypassed on the MAX to avoid negating the purpose of MCAS.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/software-fix-will-address-most-recent-max-issue|title=Software Fix Will Address Most Recent MAX Issue|last1=Broderick|first1=Sean|date=August 1, 2019|work=Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref> Boeing also said that it agreed with additional requirements that the FAA required it to fulfill, and added that it was working toward resolving the safety risk. It will not offer the MAX for certification until all requirements have been satisfied.<ref name=\"Boeing 737 MAX software\" />\n\n==== Computer redundancy ====\n{{As of|2019}}, the two flight control computers of Boeing 737 never cross-checked each other's operations; i.e., each was a single non-redundant channel. This lack of robustness existed since the early implementation and persisted for decades.<ref name=\"Seattle Times 20190801\" /> The updated flight control system will use both flight control computers and compare their outputs. This switch to a [[fail-safe]] two-channel [[Redundancy (engineering)|redundant]] system, with each computer using an independent set of sensors, is a radical change from the architecture used on 737s since the introduction on the older model 737\u2013300 in the 1980s. Up to the MAX in its prior to groundings version, the system alternates between computers after each flight.<ref name=\"Seattle Times 20190801\" /> The two computers architecture allowed switching in flight if the operating computer failed, thus increasing availability. In the revised architecture, Boeing required the two computers to monitor each other so that each one can vet the other.<ref name=\"levin\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-08/delays-in-boeing-max-return-began-with-near-crash-in-simulator|title=Delays in Boeing Max Return Began With Near-Crash in Simulator|last=Levin|first=Alan|date=2019-11-08|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n==== Trim system malfunction indicator ====\nIn January 2020, during flight testing, Boeing discovered a problem with an indicator light; the defect was traced to the \"redesign the two flight computers that control the 737 Max to make them more resilient to failure\".  The indicator, which signals a problem with the trim system, can be turned on longer than intended by design.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boeing Fixing New Software Bug on Max; Key Test Flight Nears|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-06/boeing-identifies-new-software-problem-on-grounded-737-max-jet|date=2020-02-06|work=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/6/21126364/boeing-737-max-software-glitch-flaw-problem|title=Boeing finds another software problem on the 737 Max|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=2020-02-06|website=The Verge|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n\n=== Runaway stabilizer and manual trim ===\nIn February 2016, the EASA certified the MAX with the expectation that pilot procedures and training would clearly explain unusual situations in which the seldom used manual trim wheel would be required to trim the plane, i.e. adjust the angle of the nose; however, the original flight manual did not mention those situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.easa.europa.eu/sites/default/files/dfu/IM.A.120%20Boeing737%20TCDS%20APPENDIX%20ISS%2010.pdf|title=Explanatory Note to TCDS IM.A.120 \u2013 Boeing 737|date=May 24, 2019|website=[[European Union Aviation Safety Agency]] (EASA)|access-date=}}</ref> The EASA certification document referred to simulations whereby the electric thumb switches were ineffective to properly trim the MAX under certain conditions. The EASA document said that after flight testing, because the thumb switches could not always control trim on their own, the FAA was concerned by whether the 737 MAX system complied with regulations.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ethiopia-airplane-regulator-insight-idUSKCN1RA0DP|title=Regulators knew before crashes that 737 MAX trim control was confusing in some conditions: document|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> The American Airlines flight manual contains a similar notice regarding the thumb switches but does not specify conditions where the manual wheel may be needed.<ref name=\":23\" />\n\nBoeing's CEO Muilenburg, when asked about the non-disclosure of MCAS, cited the \"runaway stabilizer trim\" procedure as part of the training manual. He added that Boeing's bulletin pointed to that existing flight procedure. Boeing views the \"runaway stabilizer trim\" checklist as a memory item for pilots. Mike Sinnett, vice president and general manager for the Boeing New Mid-Market Airplane (NMA) since July 2019, repeatedly described the procedure as a \"memory item\".<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeings-emergency-procedure-for-737-max-may-have-failed-on-ethiopian-flight/|title=Why Boeing's emergency directions may have failed to save 737 MAX|date=2019-04-03|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-09-27|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref> However, some airlines view it as an item for the quick reference card.<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/checklists-come-into-focus-as-pace-setter-for-737-max-return/|title=Checklists come into focus as pace-setter for 737 Max return|date=2019-10-09|website=The Air Current|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> The FAA issued a recommendation about memory items in an Advisory Circular, ''Standard Operating Procedures and Pilot Monitoring Duties for Flight Deck Crewmembers'': \"Memory items should be avoided whenever possible. If the procedure must include memory items, they should be clearly identified, emphasized in training, less than three items, and should not contain conditional decision steps.\"<ref name=\":36\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.faa.gov/documentlibrary/media/advisory_circular/ac_120-71b.pdf|title=Standard Operating Procedures and Pilot Monitoring Duties for Flight Deck Crewmembers|date=January 10, 2017|publisher=FAA|isbn=|series=Advisory Circulars|location=|pages=|id=AC 120-71B}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Boeing told airlines that MCAS could not be overcome by pulling back on the control column to stop a runaway trim as on previous generation 737s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/03/world/asia/lion-air-plane-crash-pilots.html|title=After a Lion Air 737 Max Crashed in October, Questions About the Plane Arose|last=Glanz|first=James|date=2019-02-03|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-07-27|last2=Creswell|first2=Julie|issn=0362-4331|last3=Kaplan|first3=Thomas|last4=Wichter|first4=Zach}}</ref> Nevertheless, confusion continued: the safety committee of a major U.S. airline misled its pilots by telling that the MCAS could be overcome by \"applying opposite control-column input to activate the column cutout switches\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviationweek.com/boeing-737-max-what-happened-and-what-now|title=Boeing 737 MAX: What Happened, And What Now?|publisher=Aviation Week Network|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref> Former pilot and [[CBS Corporation|CBS]] aviation & safety expert [[Chesley Sullenberger]] testified, \"The logic was that when MCAS was activated, it had to be, and must not be prevented.\"<ref name=\"sullysullenberger.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sullysullenberger.com/my-testimony-today-before-the-house-subcommittee-on-aviation/|title=My Testimony Today Before the House Subcommittee on Aviation|date=2019-06-19|website=Sully Sullenberger|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref> In October, Sullenberger wrote, \"These emergencies did not present as a classic runaway stabilizer problem, but initially as ambiguous unreliable airspeed and altitude situations, masking MCAS.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sullysullenberger.com/my-letter-to-the-editor-of-new-york-times-magazine/|title=My Letter to the Editor of New York Times Magazine|date=2019-10-13|website=Sully Sullenberger|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn a legal complaint against Boeing, the Southwest Airlines Pilot Association states:<ref>{{Cite book|title=PLAINTIFF'S ORIGINAL PETITION, SWAPA vs. Boeing|last=|first=|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><blockquote>An MCAS failure is not like a runaway stabilizer. A runaway stabilizer has continuous un-commanded movement of the tail, whereas MCAS is not continuous and pilots (theoretically) can counter the nose-down movement, after which MCAS would move the aircraft tail down again. Moreover, unlike runaway stabilizer, MCAS disables the control column response that 737 pilots have grown accustomed to and relied upon in earlier generations of 737 aircraft.</blockquote>\n\nIn May 2019, ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' reported that the two stabilizer cutoff switches on the MAX operate differently than on the earlier 737 NG. On previous aircraft, one cutoff switch deactivates the thumb buttons on the control yoke that pilots use to move the horizontal stabilizer; the other cutoff switch disables automatic control (as from autopilot) to move the stabilizer in the tail. On the MAX, both switches do the same thing: they cut off all electric power to the stabilizer, both from the yoke buttons and from an automatic system, like MCAS. With all power to the stabilizer cut, pilots have no choice but to use the mechanical trim wheel in the center console.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-altered-key-switches-in-737-max-cockpit-limiting-ability-to-shut-off-mcas/|title=Boeing altered key switches in 737 MAX cockpit, limiting ability to shut off MCAS|date=2019-05-10|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> However, as pilots pull on the 737 controls to raise the nose of the aircraft, aerodynamic forces on the elevator create an opposing force, effectively paralyzing the jackscrew mechanism.<ref\n      name=\"jscrew\">{{Cite web\n | url=              https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/vestigal-design-issue-clouds-737-max-crash-investigations/|title=Vestigal design issue clouds 737 MAX crash investigations\n | date=            2019-04-04\n    }}</ref>> It becomes very difficult for pilots to hand crank the trim wheel.<ref\n  name=\"jscrew\"/> The problem was encountered on earlier 737 versions, and a \"roller coaster\" emergency technique for handling the flight condition was documented in 1982 for the 737-200 but did not appear in training documentation for later versions (including the MAX).<ref\n  name=\"jscrew\"/>\n\nDuring the groundings, special flights to reposition MAX aircraft to storage locations, as per 14 CFR \u00a7 21.197, flew at lower [[flight level|altitude]] and with [[Flap (aeronautics)|flaps]] extended to circumvent MCAS activation, rather than using the recovery procedure after the fact. Such flights required a certain pilot qualification as well as permission from corresponding regulators, and with no other cabin crew or passengers.<ref name=\"LII / Legal Information Institute\">{{cite web |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/14/21.197 |title=14 CFR \u00a7 21.197 - Special flight permits. |publisher=LII / Legal Information Institute |access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref><ref name=\"simpleflying.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://simpleflying.com/norwegian-boeing-737-max-flight/|title=Norwegian Flies Boeing 737 MAX Over Europe For Storage Purposes|date=2019-06-12|website=Simple Flying|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==== Horizontal stabilizer actuator ====\nThe horizontal stabilizer is fitted with a conventional [[elevator (aeronautics)|elevator]] for flight control. However it is itself all-moving about a single pivot and can be [[trim (aircraft)|trimmed]] to adjust its angle. The trim is actuated via a [[jackscrew]] mechanism.\n\n====Slippage concern====\nSylvain Alarie and Gilles Primeau, experts on the horizontal stabilizers, observed anomalies in the data from the aircraft data recorders: a progressive shift of 0.2 degrees of the horizontal stabilizer, before the crash. \"It may not seem like much, but it is an order of magnitude higher than what is normally allowed when designing systems like these\", says Gilles Primeau. They say that the movements are easily observable, and disallowed according to Regulation 395A. These anomalies raise fundamental questions about this jack screw, which controls the horizontal stabilizer since the beginning of the 737 models, first certified in 1967.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1382157/boeing-737-max-experts-questions-enquete-verin-systeme-anomalie-aeronautique|title=Des r\u00e9v\u00e9lations troublantes sur le Boeing 737 MAX 8|last=ICI.Radio-Canada.ca|first=Zone \u00c9conomie-|website=Radio-Canada.ca|language=fr-ca|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\nThese slips are particularly visible on flight ET302: \"While there is no MCAS command, and no control of the pilots, we see a movement of the jack screw which controls the horizontal stabilizer, we see a slip. And at the very end of the flight, the jack screw starts to slide again with an increase in the speed of the plane and its dive,\" says Alarie.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nSince its original design, the 737 has become 61% heavier, 24% longer, and 40% wider, and its engines twice as powerful.\nThese experts are concerned that the loads on the jack screw have potentially increased since the creation of the 737. By regulations, the controls must be designed for 125% of the foreseeable loads.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airinsight.com/more-bad-news-for-boeing-over-the-weekend/|title=November 2019: More Bad News for Boeing over the Weekend|date=2019-11-11|access-date=2019-11-11|website=airinsight.com|last=Arvai|first=Ernest}}\n</ref> These experts have raised concerns about the motors possibly overheating in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Boeing a-t-il fait preuve de n\u00e9gligence?|trans-title=Was Boeing negligent?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BbY5P-ylYS4|language=fr|access-date=2019-11-14|last=|first=|date=April 1, 2019|publisher=Radio-Canada info}}</ref>\n\n====Manual trim stiffness====\nIn the early 1980s a problem was found with the 737-200 model. When the elevator operated to raise or lower the nose, it set up a strong force on the trim jackscrew which opposed any corrective force from the control systems. When attempting to correct an unwanted deflection using the manual trim wheel, exerting enough hand force to overcome the force exerted by the elevator became increasingly difficult as speed and deflection increased and the jack screw effectively jammed in place.<ref name=\"ostrower\">Jon Ostrower; \"[https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/vestigal-design-issue-clouds-737-max-crash-investigations/ Vestigial design issue clouds 737 Max crash investigations]\", ''The Air Current'', April 4, 2019. (retrieved November 21, 2019)</ref>\n\nA workaround was developed called the \"roller coaster\" technique. Counter-intuitively, to correct an excessive deflection causing a dive the pilot first pushes the nose down further, before easing back to gently raise the nose again. During this easing back period, the elevator deflection reduces or even reverses, its force on the jackscrew does likewise and the manual trim eases up. The workaround was included in the pilot's emergency procedures and in the training schedule.<ref name=\"ostrower\"/>\n\nHowever while the 737 Max has a similar jackscrew mechanism the \"roller coaster\" technique has been dropped from the pilot information. During the events leading to the two Max crashes, the stiffness of the manual trim wheel repeatedly prevented manual trim adjustment to correct the MCAS-induced nose-down pitching. The issue has been brought to the notice of the DoJ criminal inquiry into the 737 Max crashes.<ref name=\"ostrower\"/>\n\nIn simulator tests of [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]] flight scenario, the trim wheel was \"impossible\" to move when one of the pilots would instinctively pull up from the nosedives. It takes 15 turns to manually trim the aircraft one degree, and up to 40 turns to bring the trim back to neutral from the nose down position caused by MCAS.<ref>{{Cite news |url= https://www.flightglobal.com/safety/simulator-tests-demonstrate-737-max-manual-trim-difficulties/137651.article |title= Simulator tests demonstrate 737 Max manual trim difficulties |last= Hemmerdinger |first= Jon |website= FlightGlobal |date= 2020-04-02}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite video |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QytfYyHmxtc |title= Rogue Boeing 737 Max planes \u2018with minds of their own\u2019 |author= 60 Minutes Australia |date= May 5, 2019 |via= YouTube |quote= MCAS was designed using data from only one of the sensors because we knew the FAA would not have certified a two sensor system without level D [simulator] training}}\n* {{cite video |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H2tuKiiznsY|title=The real reason Boeing's new plane crashed twice |author= [[Vox (website)#Video|Vox Videos]] |date= Apr 15, 2019|via= Youtube}}\n* {{Cite video |author= Mentour Pilot|title=Boeing 737 Unable to Trim!! Cockpit video (Full flight sim)|date=2019-04-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aoNOVlxJmow|via= Youtube}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite web |url= https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-software-updates.page |title= The 737 MAX MCAS Software Enhancement |publisher= Boeing}}\n* {{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/05/06/safety-was-just-given-inside-boeings-boardroom-amid-max-crisis/ |title= 'Safety was just a given': Inside Boeing's boardroom amid the 737 Max crisis |author= Douglas MacMillan |date= May 5, 2019 |work= Washington Post}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/engineers-say-boeing-pushed-to-limit-safety-testing-in-race-to-certify-planes-including-737-max/ |title= Engineers say Boeing pushed to limit safety testing in race to certify planes, including 737 MAX |date= May 5, 2019 |author1= Dominic Gates |author2= Mike Baker |work= The Seattle Times}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/10/04/bjorns-corner-fly-by-steel-or-electrical-wire-part-11/ | title=Bjorn\u2019s Corner: Fly by steel or electrical wire, Part 11|last=|date=2019-10-04|website=Leeham News and Analysis|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-07}} Design of a pitch stability augmentation system.\n* {{cite news |url= https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/new-document-in-737-max-investigation-points-to-chaos-pressure-in-mcas-development/ |title= New document in 737 Max investigation points to chaos, pressure in MCAS development |date= Oct 18, 2019 |author= Jon Ostrower |work= The Air Current}}\n\n{{Boeing}}\n\n[[Category:Boeing]]\n[[Category:Aircraft controls]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Automated flight control feature developed by Boeing, contributing to the 737 MAX crashes}}\n[[File:Trimmable horizontal stabiliser.JPG|thumb|Movable horizontal stabilizer on an [[Embraer ERJ-170]]]]\n\n<section begin=summary/>The <noinclude>'''</noinclude>{{No selflink|Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System}} (MCAS) <noinclude>'''</noinclude> is a [[flight control law]] (software) embedded into the [[Boeing 737 MAX]] [[flight control system]] which attempts to mimic [[Aircraft flight control system |pitching]] behavior similar to aircraft in the previous generation of the series, the [[Boeing 737 NG]]. When MCAS detects that the aircraft is operating in manual flight, with flaps up, at an elevated angle of attack (AoA), it adjusts the horizontal stabilizer trim to add positive force feedback (a \"nose heavy\" feel), through the control column, so the pilot will not inadvertently pull the airplane up too steeply, potentially causing a [[Stall (fluid dynamics)|stall]]. Contrary to descriptions in news reports, however, Boeing claims that MCAS is not an anti-stall system. Stabilizer movement commanded by MCAS pushes down the nose of the airplane automatically without pilot input.\n\nMCAS on the MAX was designed to activate using input from only one of the airplane's two angle of attack sensors, making the system susceptible to a [[single point of failure]]. Boeing omitted a description of MCAS from MAX flight manuals, leaving pilots unaware of the system when the airplane entered service.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Laris |first1=Michael |title=Changes to flawed Boeing 737 Max were kept from pilots, DeFazio says |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/changes-to-flawed-boeing-737-max-were-kept-from-pilots-defazio-says/2019/06/19/553522f0-92bc-11e9-aadb-74e6b2b46f6a_story.html |website=The Washington Post |accessdate=29 February 2020 |date=June 19, 2019}}</ref> In April 2019, Boeing admitted that MCAS played a role in the fatal crashes of [[Lion Air Flight 610]] and [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]]. The first time Boeing publicly revealed the existence of MCAS on the 737 MAX was in a message to airline operators and other aviation interests on November 10, 2018, twelve days after the Lion Air crash.<ref name=\"AvHerald\">{{cite web |last1=Hradecky |first1=Simon |title=Crash: Lion B38M near Jakarta on Oct 29th 2018, aircraft lost height and crashed into Java Sea, wrong AoA data |url=http://avherald.com/h?article=4bf90724/0009&opt=0 |website=The Aviation Herald |accessdate=2 March 2020 |date=January 14, 2019}}</ref> Boeing had also been aware of other software issues that suppressed a crucial AoA disagree message. With no knowledge of MCAS and its behavior, the pilots of the Lion Air flight, the first to crash, were at a disadvantage when attempting to respond to the system's erroneous activation. Procedures emphasized by Boeing and the [[U.S. Federal Aviation Administration|FAA]] did not prevent the later Ethiopian Airlines crash, which led to {{No selflink|Boeing 737 MAX groundings|the worldwide grounding}} of the airliner. \n\nMCAS was first deployed on the Boeing [[KC-46]] Air Force tanker, where it \"similarly moves the stabilizer in a wind-up turn\".<ref name=\"seattletimes.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/times-watchdog/the-inside-story-of-mcas-how-boeings-737-max-system-gained-power-and-lost-safeguards/|title=The inside story of MCAS: How Boeing's 737 MAX system gained power and lost safeguards|date=2019-06-22|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-24}}</ref> Unlike the 737 MAX, however, MCAS could be overridden on the KC-46 by pulling back on its control column. The Wall Street Journal reported in May 2019 that Boeing failed to share information about that issue for \"about a year\" before the Lion Air crash in Indonesia.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Wall Street Journal |page=A1 | title=Boeing Knew of Problem for a Year |author1=Andy Pasztor |author2= Andrew Tangel |author3=Alison Sider |date=May 6, 2019}}</ref>\n<section end=\"summary\" />\n\n== Introduction ==\n<!-- Affected four system elements: 1. Avionics (Computer displays, AoA alert & indicator, etc.), 2. Flight controls (MCAS, horizontal stabilizer, manual trim, etc.), 3. Lightning protections (foil) and 4. Electrical systems (wiring bundles) --><!-- This shows safety measure related to MCAS/AoA by Boeing/FAA after the first crash but was not enough to avoid the second crash -->\n\n[[File:Adjustable stabilizer.svg|thumb|The MAX uses an adjustable stabilizer, moved by a jackscrew, to provide the required pitch trim forces. Generic stabilizer illustrated.]]\n\nThe {{No selflink|Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System}} (MCAS) [[flight control law]] was implemented on the 737 MAX to mitigate the aircraft's tendency to [[Aircraft principal axes|pitch up]] because of the aerodynamic effect of its larger, heavier, and more powerful CFM [[CFM International LEAP|LEAP-1B engines]] and nacelles.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2018/11/14/boeings-automatic-trim-for-the-737-max-was-not-disclosed-to-the-pilots/|title=Boeing's automatic trim for the 737 MAX was not disclosed to the Pilots|date=2018-11-14|website=Leeham News and Analysis}}</ref> The stated goal of MCAS, according to Boeing, was to provide consistent aircraft handling characteristics at elevated angles of attack in certain unusual flight conditions only and hence make the 737 MAX perform similarly to its immediate predecessor, the [[737NG]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/737-max-updates/737-max-answers//|title=Your 737 MAX Questions. Answered: 5. What is MCAS?|publisher=Boeing}}</ref>\n\n{{multiple image\n |align = center\n |width = \n |image1 = Boeing 737-200 (Brasilia Air Base) JT8D.jpg\n |width1 = 180\n |caption1 = 737-200 JT8D engine with original cowling design\n |image2 = CFM-56 Lauda 737.jpg\n |width2 = 177\n |caption2 = 737-800 (Next Generation) CFM56 engine with ovoid inlet\n |image3 = Boeing 737-9 MAX CFM LEAP-1B PAS.jpg\n |width3 = 184\n |caption3 = 737 MAX 9 CFM LEAP-1B engine with 787-derived engine chevrons\n}}\n\n==== MCAS's role in the accidents ====\n[[File:Lion Air Flight 610.svg|thumb|The tracking data of Lion Air Flight 610 from [[Flightradar24]]]] [[File:Vertical airspeeds of Boeing Max 737s in 2018-2019 crashes.jpg|alt=Vertical airspeeds of Boeing Max 737s in 2018-2019 crashes|thumb|The vertical airspeeds of the Boeing 737 MAX 8s involved in the JT 610 and ET 302 crashes]]\nInvestigators determined that MCAS was triggered by falsely high [[angle of attack]] (AoA) inputs, as if the plane had [[Aircraft principal axes|pitched]] up excessively. On both flights, shortly after takeoff, MCAS repeatedly actuated the [[horizontal stabilizer]] [[Trim tab|trim]] motor to push down the airplane nose.<ref name=\":12\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-software-updates.page|title=737 MAX software update|publisher=Boeing}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://saemobilus.sae.org/automated-connected/news/2019/04/boeing-flies-a-737-max-7-with-mcas-software-update|title=Boeing flies first 737 MAX 7 with MCAS software update|website=saemobilus.sae.org|access-date=2019-06-06}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.intelligent-aerospace.com/home/article/16537707/the-boeing-737-max-is-the-problem-with-the-plane-or-the-pilots|title=The Boeing 737 MAX: Is the problem with the plane or the pilots?|date=2019-03-12|website=Intelligent Aerospace|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://graphics.reuters.com/ETHIOPIA-AIRLINE-CONTROLS/0100916V1NZ/index.html|title=Change to 737 MAX controls may have imperiled planes|publisher=Reuters|access-date=2019-07-03}}</ref> [[Tracking (commercial airline flight)|Satellite data]] for the flights, [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302|ET 302]] and [[Lion Air Flight 610|JT 610]], showed that the planes struggled to gain altitude.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-03-13/doomed-737-caught-on-satellite-data-that-could-aid-investigation|title=Clue Linking Mysterious Boeing 737 Max Disasters Came From Space|last1=Levin|first1=Alan|website=Bloomberg News|access-date=June 6, 2019}}</ref> Pilots reported difficulty controlling the airplane and asked to return to the airport.<ref name=\":4\">{{cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/canada-grounds-boeing-737-max-8-leaving-us-as-last-major-user-of-plane/2019/03/13/25ac2414-459d-11e9-90f0-0ccfeec87a61_story.html |title=FAA's emergency order grounding Boeing jets came after the agency identified similarities between crashes in Ethiopia, Indonesia |first1=Luz |last1=Lazo |first2=Michael |last2=Laris |first3=Lori |last3=Aratani |first4=Damian |last4=Paletta |date=March 13, 2019 |work=[[The Washington Post]] |access-date=March 13, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/20/world/asia/lion-air-crash-boeing.html |title=Confusion, Then Prayer, in Cockpit of Doomed Lion Air Jet |last1=Beech |first1=Hannah |date=March 20, 2019 |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date=March 21, 2019 |last2=Suhartono |first2=Muktita}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, 2019, after China had grounded the aircraft,<ref name=\"sea-tim-03-17-19\">{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/failed-certification-faa-missed-safety-issues-in-the-737-max-system-implicated-in-the-lion-air-crash/|title=Flawed analysis, failed oversight: How Boeing, FAA certified the suspect 737 MAX flight control system|last1=Gates|first1=Dominic|date=March 18, 2019|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=March 19, 2019}}</ref> Boeing published some details of new system requirements for the MCAS software and for the cockpit displays, which it began implementing in the wake of the prior accident five months earlier:<ref name=\":12\" />\n* If the two AOA sensors disagree with the flaps retracted, MCAS will not activate and an indicator will alert the pilots.\n* If MCAS is activated in non-normal conditions, it will only \"provide one input for each elevated AOA event.\"\n* Flight crew will be able to counteract MCAS by pulling back on the column.\n\nOn March 27, [[Daniel Elwell]], the acting administrator of the FAA, testified before the Senate Committee on Commerce, Science, and Transportation, saying that on January 21, \"Boeing submitted a proposed MCAS software enhancement to the FAA for certification. ... the FAA has tested this enhancement to the 737 MAX flight control system in both the simulator and the aircraft. The testing, which was conducted by FAA flight test engineers and flight test pilots, included aerodynamic stall situations and recovery procedures.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.transportation.gov/content/state-airline-safety-federal-oversight-commercial-aviation|title=The State of Airline Safety: Federal Oversight of Commercial Aviation|date=March 27, 2019|publisher=U.S. [[Department of Transportation]] (DOT)|access-date=July 27, 2019|quote=On January 21, 2019, Boeing submitted a proposed MCAS software enhancement to the FAA for certification. To date, the FAA has tested this enhancement to the 737 MAX flight control system in both the simulator and the aircraft. The testing, which was conducted by FAA flight test engineers and flight test pilots, included aerodynamic stall situations and recovery procedures.  The FAA's ongoing review of this software installation and training is an agency priority, as will be the roll-out of any software, training, or other measures to operators of the 737 MAX.}}</ref> After a series of delays, the updated MCAS software was released to the FAA in May 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeings-software-fix-for-737-max-still-weeks-away-from-delivery-to-faa/|title=Boeing's software fix for 737 MAX still weeks away from delivery to FAA|date=2019-04-01|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-04-02|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theregister.co.uk/2019/03/19/boeing_repeats_737_max_software_update_promises/|title=Boeing big cheese repeats pledge of 737 Max software updates following fatal crashes|last=Corfield|first=Gareth|date=March 19, 2019|work=[[The Register]]|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> On May 16, Boeing announced that the completed software update was awaiting approval from the FAA.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/16/politics/737-max-boeing-software-fix/index.html|title=Boeing says it has completed 737 Max software fix|last=Rappard|first=Anna-Maja|last2=Wallace|first2=Gregory|publisher=[[CNN]]|access-date=2019-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/05/16/boeing-says-max-update-held-up-by-faa-questions/|title=Boeing says 737 Max update is being held up by FAA questions|last=MacMillan|first=Douglas|date=May 16, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=May 19, 2019}}</ref> The flight software underwent 360 hours of testing on 207 flights.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/05/16/boeing-says-it-has-completed-the-development-of-updated-software-for-the-737-max.html|title=Boeing says it has completed a software update for 737 Max anti-stall system linked to fatal crashes|last=Josephs|first=Leslie|date=2019-05-16|publisher=CNBC|access-date=2019-05-27}}</ref> Boeing also updated existing crew procedures.<ref name=\":12\" /> The implementation of MCAS has been found to disrupt autopilot operations.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20190705\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-05/europe-sets-out-demands-for-boeing-before-max-can-fly-again|title=Boeing 737 Max's Autopilot Has Problem, European Regulators Find|date=2019-07-05|access-date=2019-07-06|publisher=Bloomberg News}}</ref>\n\nOn April 4, 2019 Boeing publicly acknowledged that MCAS played a role in both accidents.<ref name=\"WashPost4apr2019\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/04/04/boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-apologizes-lives-lost-ethiopian-indonesian-plane-crashes/|title=Boeing CEO apologizes for lives lost and acknowledges role of company's flight-control system in two crashes|last1=Gregg|first1=Aaron|date=April 4, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]}}</ref>\n\n==== Purpose of MCAS and the stabilizer trim system  ====\n<!-- MCAS description (what MCAS is and is not) -->\nThe FAA and Boeing both refuted media reports describing MCAS as an [[Stall (fluid dynamics)|anti-stall]] system, which Boeing asserted it is distinctly not.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/live-news/faa-hearing-today-live-stream-updates-boeing-737-max-8-mcas-senate-commerce-committee-2019-03-27/|title=Congress holds fiery hearings on Boeing 737 Max 8 approval|website=[[CBS News]]|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeing-737-max-mcas-explained|title=The Boeing 737 MAX MCAS Explained|date=March 20, 2019|work=[[Aviation Week & Space Technology]]|first1=Sean |last1=Broderick |first2=Guy |last2=Norris |first3=Graham |last3=Warwick }}</ref><ref name=\"tac\">{{cite news|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/what-is-the-boeing-737-max-maneuvering-characteristics-augmentation-system-mcas-jt610/|title=What is the Boeing 737 Max Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System|last1=Ostrower|first1=Jon|date=November 13, 2018|access-date=March 14, 2019|website=The Air Current}}</ref> The aircraft had to perform well in a low-speed stall test.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/14/25.203 |title=14 CFR \u00a7 25.203 - Stall characteristics. |website=LII / Legal Information Institute |access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> The {{Pslink|Joint Authorities Technical Review}} \"considers that the STS/MCAS and elevator feel shift (EFS) functions could be considered as stall identification systems or stall protection systems, depending on the natural (unaugmented) stall characteristics of the aircraft\".\n\nThe JATR said, \"MCAS used the stabilizer to change the column force feel, not trim the aircraft. This is a case of using the control surface in a new way that the regulations never accounted for and should have required an issue paper for further analysis by the FAA. If the FAA technical staff had been fully aware of the details of the MCAS function, the JATR team believes the agency likely would have required an issue paper for using the stabilizer in a way that it had not previously been used; this [might have] identified the potential for the stabilizer to overpower the elevator.\"<ref name=\"Obs\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/media/attachments/Final_JATR_Submittal_to_FAA_Oct_2019.pdf|title=Boeing 737 MAX Flight Control System&nbsp;: Observations, Findings, and Recommendations|last=Hart|publisher=FAA|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref>\n\n== Description ==\n[[File:Angle attack sensor hg.jpg|thumb|an [[angle of attack]] (AOA) sensor]]\n\n=== Background ===\n<!-- what is it? -->\nThe Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System (MCAS) is a [[Flight control modes|flight control law]]<ref name=\"737 MAX SOFTWARE UPDATE\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-software-updates.page#/overview|title=737 MAX SOFTWARE UPDATE|publisher=Boeing}}</ref> built into the [[Boeing 737 MAX]]'s flight control computer, designed to help the aircraft emulate the handling characteristics of the earlier [[Boeing 737 Next Generation]]. According to an international Civil Aviation Authorities team review (JATR) commissioned by the FAA, MCAS may be a stall identification or protection system, depending on the natural (unaugmented) stall characteristics of the aircraft.<ref name=\"Obs\"/><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.faa.gov/news/updates/?newsId=93206|title=FAA Updates on Boeing 737 MAX|website=www.faa.gov|language=en-us|access-date=2019-10-19}}</ref><ref name=\":0\" /> Boeing considered MCAS part of the flight control system, and elected to not describe it in the flight manual or in training materials, based on the fundamental design philosophy of retaining commonality with the [[737NG]]. Minimizing the functional differences between the Boeing 737 MAX and Next Generation aircraft variants allowed both variants to share the same [[type rating]]. Thus, airlines can save money by employing and training one pool of pilots to fly both variants of the Boeing 737 interchangeably.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/boeing-737-max-mcas-explained|title=The Boeing 737 MAX MCAS Explained|last=Warwick|first=Graham|date=Mar 20, 2019|website=Aviation Week|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04|last4=Week}}</ref>\n\nWhen activated, MCAS directly engages the [[Stabilizer (aeronautics)|horizontal stabilizer]], thus is distinct from an anti-stall device, such as [[stick pusher]], which physically moves the pilot's control column forward and engages the airplane's [[Elevator (aeronautics)|elevators]] when the airplane is approaching a stall.\n\nBoeing's former CEO [[Dennis Muilenburg]] said \"[MCAS] has been reported or described as an anti-stall system, which it is not. It's a system that's designed to provide handling qualities for the pilot that meet pilot preferences.\"<ref name=\"BusinessInsider29apr2019\" />\n\n<!-- why? -->The 737 MAX's larger [[CFM LEAP|CFM LEAP-1B]] engines are fitted further forward and higher up than in previous models. The aerodynamic effect of its [[nacelle]]s contributes to the aircraft's tendency to [[Aircraft principal axes|pitch up]] at high [[angle of attack|angles of attack]] (AOA). The MCAS is intended to compensate in such cases, modeling the pitching behavior of previous models, and meet a certain certification requirement,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/14/25.203|title=14 CFR \u00a7 25.203 - Stall characteristics.|website=LII / Legal Information Institute|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> in order to enhance handling characteristics and thus minimizing the need for significant pilot retraining.<ref name=\"TAC13nov2018\">{{cite news|last1=Ostrower|first1=Jon|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/what-is-the-boeing-737-max-maneuvering-characteristics-augmentation-system-mcas-jt610/|title=What is the Boeing 737 Max Maneuvering Characteristics Augmentation System|date=November 13, 2018|accessdate=March 14, 2019|website=The Air Current}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Bazley |first1=Tarek |title=Control system under scrutiny after Ethiopian Airlines crash |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2019/03/control-system-scrutiny-ethiopian-airlines-crash-190311094532350.html |website=[[Al Jazeera]] |date=March 11, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"BusinessInsider29apr2019\">{{cite news |last1=Zhang |first1=Benjamin |title=Boeing's CEO explains why the company didn't tell 737 Max pilots about the software system that contributed to 2 fatal crashes |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/boeings-ceo-on-why-737-max-pilots-not-told-of-mcas-2019-4 |work=Business Insider |date=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe software code for the MCAS function and the computer for executing the software are built to Boeing's specifications by [[Collins Aerospace|Collins Aerospace, formerly Rockwell Collins]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/boeings-737-max-design-contains-fingerprints-of-hundreds-of-suppliers/2019/04/05/44f22024-57ab-11e9-8ef3-fbd41a2ce4d5_story.html|title=Boeing's 737 Max design contains fingerprints of hundreds of suppliers|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=2019-06-04}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Boeing 737-524, Transaero Airlines AN2037840 (stab trim).jpg|thumb|upright|The trim wheel and cutoff switches in a previous generation cockpit]]\n\nAs an automated corrective measure, the MCAS was given full authority to bring the aircraft nose down, and could not be overridden by pilot resistance against the control wheel as on previous versions of the 737.<ref name=\"sullyTestimony\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sullysullenberger.com/my-testimony-today-before-the-house-subcommittee-on-aviation/|title=My Testimony Today Before the House Subcommittee on Aviation|date=2019-06-19|website=Sully Sullenberger|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref> Following the Lion Air accident, Boeing issued an Operations Manual Bulletin (OMB)<ref>{{cite web |title=Boeing Statement on Operations Manual Bulletin |url=https://boeing.mediaroom.com/news-releases-statements?item=130327 |publisher=Boeing |accessdate=2 July 2019 |date=November 6, 2018}}</ref> on November 6, 2019 to  outline the many indications and effects resulting from erroneous AOA data and provided instructions to turn off the motorized trim system for the remainder of the flight, and trim manually instead. Until Boeing supplemented the manuals<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.flyingmag.com/faa-emergency-airworthiness-directive-boeing-737-max-8/|title=FAA Issues Emergency AD Against Boeing 737 Max 8|website=Flying|language=en|access-date=2019-07-02}}</ref> and training, pilots were unaware of the existence of MCAS due to its omission from the crew manual and no coverage in training.<ref name=\"sullyTestimony\"/>  Boeing first publicly named and revealed the existence of MCAS on the 737 MAX in a message to airline operators and other aviation interests on November 10, 2018, twelve days after the Lion Air crash.<ref name=\"AvHerald\"/>\n\n=== Inception ===\nThe MCAS design parameters originally envisioned automated corrective actions to be taken in cases of high AoA and [[G-force]]s beyond normal flight conditions. [[Test pilot]]s routinely push aircraft to such extremes, as the FAA requires airplanes to perform as expected. Before the MCAS, test pilot Ray Craig determined the plane did not fly smoothly, in part due to the larger engines. Craig would have preferred an [[Aerodynamics|aerodynamic]] solution, but Boeing decided to implement a control law in software.\n\nAccording to a news report from the Wall Street Journal, engineers who had worked on the KC-46A Pegasus tanker, which includes an MCAS function, suggested MCAS to the design team.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/before-737-max-boeings-flight-control-system-included-key-safeguards-11569754800|title=WSJ News Exclusive {{!}} Before 737 MAX, Boeing\u2019s Flight-Control System Included Key Safeguards|last=Tangel|first=Alison Sider and Andrew|website=WSJ|language=en-US|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref>\n\nWith the MCAS implemented, new test pilot Ed Wilson said the \"MAX wasn\u2019t handling well when nearing stalls at low speeds\u201d and recommended MCAS to apply across a broader range of flight conditions. This required the MCAS to function under normal G-forces and, at stalling speeds, deflect the vertical trim more rapidly and to a greater extent\u2014but now it reads a single AoA sensor.\n\nThe FAA did not conduct a safety analysis on the changes. It had already approved the previous version of MCAS, and the agency's rules did not require it to take a second look because the changes did not affect how the plane operated in extreme situations.\n<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/06/01/business/boeing-737-max-crash.html|title=Boeing Built Deadly Assumptions Into 737 Max, Blind to a Late Design Change|last=Nicas|first=Jack|date=2019-06-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-06-07|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Gelles|first3=David|last4=Glanz|first4=James}}</ref>\n\n=== Safety engineering and human factors ===\nAs with any other equipment on board an aircraft, the FAA approves a functional \"design assurance level\"  corresponding to the consequences of a failure, using the [[SAE International]] standards [[ARP4754]] and [[ARP4761|ARP4761.]] MCAS was designated a \"hazardous failure\" system. This classification corresponds to failures causing \"a large reduction in safety margins\" or \"serious or fatal injury to a relatively small number of the occupants\", but nothing \"catastrophic\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/5/2/18518176/boeing-737-max-crash-problems-human-error-mcas-faa|title=The many human errors that brought down the Boeing 737 Max|last=Campbell|first=Darryl|date=2019-05-02|website=The Verge|access-date=2019-06-13}}</ref>\n\nThe MCAS was designed with the assumption, approved by FAA, that pilots would react to an unexpected activation within three seconds.<ref name=\"seattletimes.com\"/>\n\n=== MCAS on the Boeing KC-46 ===\nMCAS exists in a different form on the [[Boeing KC-46 Pegasus]], an [[aerial refueling]] tanker that is fundamentally a [[Boeing 767|Boeing 767-2C]]. The system takes input on dual redundant angle of attack sensors; it will disengage with stick input by the pilot. The Air Force stated that \"The KC-46 has protections that ensure pilot manual inputs have override priority\" and that it \"does not fly the models of aircraft involved in the recent accidents\" and that it is \"reviewing our procedures and training as part of our normal and ongoing review process.\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.airforcemag.com/Features/Pages/2019/March%202019/USAF-Reviewing-Training-After-MAX-8-Crashes-KC-46-Uses-Similar-MCAS-System.aspx|title=USAF Reviewing Training After MAX 8 Crashes; KC-46 Uses Similar MCAS|website=www.airforcemag.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-03-23|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323043919/http://www.airforcemag.com/Features/Pages/2019/March%25202019/USAF-Reviewing-Training-After-MAX-8-Crashes-KC-46-Uses-Similar-MCAS-System.aspx|archive-date=2019-03-23|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== MCAS technology readiness ==\nBoeing presented MCAS to the FAA as being existing technology, avoiding  deeper scrutiny. The U.S. House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee provided all 43 Boeing's presentation slides in the document titled \"MCAS Development and Certification Overview.\" at the request of the Seattle Times, which noted that MCAS was not evaluated as an individual system that was \"new/novel on the MAX.\" The FAA is required to be closely involved in the testing and certification of any new and novel features on an aircraft.<ref>{{Cite web| url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/after-lion-air-crash-boeing-doubled-down-on-faulty-737-max-assumptions/|title=After Lion Air crash, Boeing doubled down on faulty 737 MAX assumptions|date=2019-11-08|website=The Seattle Times|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref> Aerospace reporter Dominic Gates summarized: \"The justification given was a doubtful comparison with the 767 tanker\".\n\nJust before entering certification, the functional requirements for MCAS were still changing. Boeing modified MCAS so that it intervened more strongly and at lower airspeeds than originally planned. \"Inadvertently, the door was now opened to serious system misbehavior during the busy and stressful moments right after takeoff\", said Jenkins of ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/boeing-vs-technological-chaos-11572998029|title=Boeing vs. Technological Chaos|last=Jenkins|first=Holman W. jr.|date=2019-11-05|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\nThe JATR found the technology unprecedented: \"If the FAA technical staff had been fully aware of the details of the MCAS function, the JATR team believes the agency likely would have required an issue paper for using the stabilizer in a way that it had not previously been used. MCAS used the stabilizer to change the column force feel, not trim the aircraft. This is a case of using the control surface in a new way that the regulations never accounted for and should have required an issue paper for further analysis by the FAA. If an issue paper had been required, the JATR team believes it likely would have identified the potential for the stabilizer to overpower the elevator.\"<ref name=\"Obs\" />\n\n== Scrutiny ==\n[[File:Lion Air Flight 610.svg|thumb|Altitude and speed of Lion Air Flight 610]]\nThe MCAS has been under scrutiny following the fatal crashes of [[Lion Air Flight 610]] and [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]] soon after takeoff. The Boeing 737 MAX global fleet has been [[Boeing 737 MAX groundings|grounded]] by all airlines and operators, and a number of functional issues have been raised.<ref name=\"Gates\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/failed-certification-faa-missed-safety-issues-in-the-737-max-system-implicated-in-the-lion-air-crash/ |title=Flawed analysis, failed oversight: How Boeing and FAA certified the suspect 737 MAX flight control system|newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|first= Dominic |last= Gates|date=March 17, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/04/05/bjorns-corner-et302-crash-report-the-first-analysis/|title=Bjorn's Corner: ET302 crash report, the first analysis|last=Fehrm|first=Bjorn|date=2019-04-05|work=Leeham News and Analysis}}</ref><ref name=\"Gates_20191029\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-ceo-must-have-answers-about-the-737-max-as-he-faces-congressional-scrutiny-this-week/ |title=Live coverage: Boeing CEO Dennis Muilenburg testifies to Congress about 737 MAX |newspaper=[[The Seattle Times]]|first= Dominic |last= Gates|date=October 29, 2019}}</ref>\n\nThe use of a single AOA sensor at any one time creates a [[single point of failure]] and leads to the possibility that a single malfunctioning sensor could produce erroneous data, cause the MCAS system to pitch the nose downward and force the aircraft into a dive.<ref name=\"https\">{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/a-lack-of-redundancies-on-737-max-system-has-baffled-even-those-who-worked-on-the-jet/|title=Lack of redundancies on Boeing 737 MAX system baffles some involved in developing the jet|last1=Baker|first1=Mike|last2=Gates|first2=Dominic|date=March 26, 2019|website=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref name=TAC13nov2018/><!--ref name=IEEE18apr2019/-->\n\nThe MCAS deflects the horizontal stabilizer four times farther than was stated in the initial safety analysis document.<ref name=\"Gates\"/> Due to the amount of trim the system applies to the horizontal stabilizer, aerodynamic forces resist pilot control effort to raise the nose. As long as the faulty AOA readings persist, a human pilot \"can quickly become exhausted trying to pull the column back\".<ref name=\"IEEE18apr2019\">{{cite news|last1=Travis|first1=Gregory|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190424114042/https://spectrum.ieee.org/aerospace/aviation/how-the-boeing-737-max-disaster-looks-to-a-software-developer|title=How the Boeing 737 Max Disaster Looks to a Software Developer|date=April 18, 2019|work=IEEE Spectrum}}</ref> In addition, switches for the horizontal stabilizer trim assist now serve a shared purpose of turning off the MCAS. In simulator sessions, pilots were stunned by the substantial effort needed to manually crank the trim wheel out of its nose down setting.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/04/03/et302-used-the-cut-out-switches-to-stop-mcas/|title=ET302 used the Cut-Out switches to stop MCAS|last=Bjorn|first=Fehrm|date=2019-04-03|website=Leeham News and Analysis}}</ref><ref name=\"Mike Baker and Dominic Gates\">{{Cite news|author=Mike Baker and Dominic Gates|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-altered-key-switches-in-737-max-cockpit-limiting-ability-to-shut-off-mcas/|title=Boeing altered key switches in 737 MAX cockpit, limiting ability to shut off MCAS|date=May 10, 2019|newspaper=The Seattle Times}}</ref><ref name=AvWeek10may2019>{{cite news |url= https://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/ethiopian-max-crash-simulator-scenario-stuns-pilots |title= Ethiopian MAX Crash Simulator Scenario Stuns Pilots |date= May 10, 2019 |author= Sean Broderick |work= Aviation Week Network}}</ref>\n\nBoeing and the FAA decided that the AOA display and an AOA disagree light, which signals if the sensors give different readings, were not critical features for safe operation.<ref name=Reuters30nov2018>{{cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-crash-boeing-aoa/optional-warning-light-could-have-aided-lion-air-engineers-before-crash-experts-idUSKCN1NZ0QL|title=Optional warning light could have aided Lion Air engineers before crash: experts|first1=Jamie|last1=Freed|first2=Eric |last2=Johnson|date=November 30, 2018|agency=Reuters}}</ref> Boeing charged extra for the addition of the AoA indicator to the primary display.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Newburger |first1=Emma |title=Crashed jets reportedly lacked key safety features because Boeing charged extra for them |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/21/crashed-boeing-jets-lacked-key-safety-features-that-were-add-ons.html |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |publisher=CNBC |date=March 21, 2019}}</ref><ref name=NYtimes21mar2019>{{cite news |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/business/boeing-safety-features-charge.html |title= Doomed Boeing Jets Lacked 2 Safety Features That Company Sold Only as Extras |first1= Hiroko |last1= Tabucho |first2= David |last2= Gelles |date= March 21, 2019 |accessdate= March 21, 2019 |work= [[The New York Times]] }}</ref> In November 2017, Boeing engineers discovered that the standard AoA disagree light cannot independently function without the optional AoA indicator software, affecting 80% of the global fleet which had not ordered the option.<ref name=\"Gelles\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/05/business/boeing-737-max-warning-light.html|title=Boeing Believed a 737 Max Warning Light Was Standard. It Wasn't.|last=Gelles|first=David|date=2019-05-05|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-05-11|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/faa-considered-grounding-boeing-737-max-planes-last-180808293.html|title=FAA considered grounding some Boeing 737 Max planes last year: source|website=news.yahoo.com|language=en-US|access-date=2019-05-11}}</ref> The software remedy was scheduled to coincide with the roll out of the elongated [[737 MAX 10]] in 2020, only to be accelerated by the [[Lion Air Flight 610|Lion Air accident]]. Furthermore, the problem had not been disclosed to the FAA until 13 months after the fact. Although it is unclear whether the indicator could have changed the  outcome for the ill-fated flights, American Airlines said the disagree indicator provided the assurance in continued operations of the airplane. \"As it turned out, that wasn't true.\" <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://apnews.com/024ba22014d647a481d52e52ab8dde61|title=Boeing wanted to wait 3 years to fix safety alert on 737 Max|last=Koenig|first=David|last2=Krisher|first2=Tom|date=2019-06-07|website=AP NEWS|access-date=2019-06-11}}</ref>\n\nBoeing CEO [[Dennis Muilenburg]] has stated that there was \"no surprise, or gap, or unknown here or something that somehow slipped through a certification process.\"<ref>{{cite news |url= https://www.bizjournals.com/wichita/news/2019/04/24/boeing-ceo-nothing-slipped-through-in-original-737.html |title= Boeing CEO: Nothing slipped through in original 737 MAX certification |author= Daniel McCoy |work= Wichita Business Journal |date= Apr 24, 2019}}</ref> On April 29, 2019 he stated the design of the aircraft was not flawed and reiterated that it was designed per Boeing's standards.<ref name=SeattleTimes29apr2019>{{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/facing-sharp-questions-boeing-ceo-refuses-to-admit-flaws-in-737-max-design/ |title= Facing sharp questions, Boeing CEO refuses to admit flaws in 737 MAX design |author= Dominic Gates |work= Seattle Times |date= Apr 29, 2019}}</ref> In a May 29 interview with CBS, Boeing admitted that it had botched the software implementation and lamented the poor communications.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/boeing-ceo-dennis-muilenburg-says-he-would-put-his-family-737-max-without-any-hesitation-exclusive-2019-05-29/|title=Boeing CEO says he would put his family in a 737 Max \"without any hesitation\"|last=May 29|first=CBS News|last2=2019|website=www.cbsnews.com|language=en|access-date=2019-06-12|last3=Pm|first3=6:50}}</ref>\n\nOn September 26, the [[National Transportation Safety Board]] criticized Boeing\u2019s inadequate testing of the 737 MAX, and pointed out that Boeing made erroneous assumptions on pilots\u2019 response to alerts in 737 MAX, triggered by activation of MCAS due to a faulty signal from an angle-of-attack sensor.<ref name=\"ntsb20190926\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/26/business/boeing-737-max-ntsb-mcas.html|title=Boeing Underestimated Cockpit Chaos on 737 Max, N.T.S.B. Says|last=Kitroeff|first=Natalie|date=2019-09-26|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-09-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/ASR1901.pdf|title=Safety Recommendation Report: Assumptions Used in the Safety Assessment Process and the Effects of Multiple Alerts and Indications on Pilot Performance|last=|first=|date=19 September 2019|website=www.ntsb.gov|publisher=NTSB|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-09-26|layurl=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Pages/ASR1901.aspx}}</ref>\n\nThe Joint Authorities Technical Review (JATR), a team commissioned by the FAA for 737 MAX investigation, concluded that FAA failed to properly review MCAS. Boeing failed to provide adequate and updated technical information regarding the MCAS system to FAA during Boeing 737 Max certification process, and had not carried out a thorough verification by [[stress-testing]] of the MCAS system.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-boeing-airplane-faa-idUSKBN1WQ0H8|title=FAA failed to properly review 737 MAX jet anti-stall system: JATR findings|date=2019-10-11|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-10-11|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/10/11/business/boeing-737-max.html|title=Review of 737 Max Certification Finds Fault With Boeing and F.A.A.|last=Gelles|first=David|date=2019-10-11|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-10-11|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nOn October 18, Boeing turned over a discussion from 2016 between two employees which revealed prior issues with the MCAS system.<ref name=\":43\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/trafficandcommuting/text-messages-show-boeing-employees-knew-in-2016-of-problems-that-turned-deadly-on-the-737-max/2019/10/18/8578c990-f1ca-11e9-89eb-ec56cd414732_story.html|title=Messages show Boeing employees knew in 2016 of problems that turned deadly on the 737 Max|last=Laris|first=Michael|date=2019-10-18|work=The Washington Post|access-date=2019-10-18}}</ref>\n\n=== NTSB === <!-- Boeing knowledge about MAX airworthiness design issues and its measure-->\n\nOn September 26, 2019, the NTSB released the results of its review of potential lapses in the design and approval of the 737 MAX.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/09/26/business/boeing-737-max-ntsb-mcas.html|title=Boeing Underestimated Cockpit Chaos on 737 Max, N.T.S.B. Says|last=Kitroeff|first=Natalie|date=2019-09-26|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-09-26|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\":31\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Reports/ASR1901.pdf|title=Safety Recommendation Report: Assumptions Used in the Safety Assessment Process and the Effects of Multiple Alerts and Indications on Pilot Performance|date=September 19, 2019|publisher=NTSB|access-date=2019-09-26|layurl=https://www.ntsb.gov/investigations/AccidentReports/Pages/ASR1901.aspx}}{{NTSB}}</ref>{{rp|page=1}}<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.ntsb.gov/news/press-releases/Pages/NR20190926.aspx|title=NTSB Issues 7 Safety Recommendations to FAA related to Ongoing Lion Air, Ethiopian Airlines Crash Investigations|website=NTSB|access-date=2019-09-30}}</ref> The NTSB report concludes that assumptions \"that Boeing used in its functional hazard assessment of uncommanded MCAS function for the 737 MAX did not adequately consider and account for the impact that multiple flight deck alerts and indications could have on pilots' responses to the hazard\". When Boeing induced a stabilizer trim input that simulated the stabilizer moving consistent with the MCAS function, \"... the specific failure modes that could lead to unintended MCAS activation (such as an erroneous high AOA input to the MCAS) were not simulated as part of these functional hazard assessment validation tests. As a result, additional flight deck effects (such as IAS DISAGREE and ALT DISAGREE alerts and stick shaker activation) resulting from the same underlying failure (for example, erroneous AOA) were not simulated and were not in the stabilizer trim safety assessment report reviewed by the NTSB.\"<ref name=\":31\" /><ref name=\":31\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ft.com/content/19781330-e5cd-11e9-b112-9624ec9edc59|title=Boeing report highlights human factors no company should ignore|last=Hill|first=Andrew|date=October 6, 2019|work=Financial Times|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nThe NTSB questioned the long-held industry and FAA practice of assuming the nearly instantaneous responses of highly trained test pilots as opposed to pilots of all levels of experience to verify [[human factors]] in aircraft safety.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/plane-tests-must-use-average-pilots-ntsb-says-after-737-max-crashes-11569506401|title=Plane Tests Must Use Average Pilots, NTSB Says After 737 MAX Crashes|last=Pasztor|first=Andy|date=September 26, 2019|access-date=2019-09-27|author-link=Andy Pasztor|url-access=subscription|website=[[The Wall Street Journal]]}}</ref> The NTSB expressed concerns that the process used to evaluate the original design needs improvement because that process is still in use to certify current and future aircraft and system designs. The FAA could for example randomly sample pools from the worldwide pilot community to get a more representative assessment of cockpit situations.<ref name=\":32\">{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/5687473/boeing-737-alarm-system/|title=Boeing Failed to Predict That Slew of 737 Max Warning Alarms Would Confuse Pilots, Investigators Say|website=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|access-date=2019-09-27}}</ref>\n<br />\n\n== Supporting systems==\nThe updates proposed by Boeing focus mostly on MCAS software.<ref name=\"737 MAX SOFTWARE UPDATE\"/> In particular, there have been no public statements regarding reverting the functionality of the stabilizer trim cutout switches to pre-MAX configuration. A veteran software engineer and experienced pilot suggested that software changes may not be enough to counter the 737 MAX's engine placement.<ref name=EETimes27mar2019>{{cite news |url= https://www.eetimes.com/document.asp?doc_id=1334482 |title= Software Won't Fix Boeing's 'Faulty' Airframe |work= [[EE Times]] |author= George Leopold |date= March 27, 2019 }}</ref> Seattle Times notes that while the new software fix Boeing has proposed \"will likely prevent this situation recurring, if the preliminary investigation confirms that the Ethiopian pilots did cut off the automatic flight-control system, this is still a nightmarish outcome for Boeing and the FAA. It would suggest the emergency procedure laid out by Boeing and passed along by the FAA after the Lion Air crash is wholly inadequate and failed the Ethiopian flight crew.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeings-emergency-procedure-for-737-max-may-have-failed-on-ethiopian-flight/|title=Why Boeing's emergency directions may have failed to save 737 MAX|date=2019-04-03|website=The Seattle Times|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-03}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2019, Jim Marko, a manager of aircraft integration and safety assessment at [[Transport Canada]] aviation regulator's National Aircraft Certification Branch questioned the readiness of MCAS. Because new problems kept emerging, he suggested to his peers at FAA, ANAC and EASA to consider the safety benefits of removing MCAS from the MAX.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/transport-canada-safety-official-urges-removal-of-mcas-from-737-max/|title=Transport Canada safety official urges removal of MCAS from 737 Max|date=2019-11-23|website=The Air Current|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\n=== Angle of Attack (AoA) ===\nAs per Boeing technical description: \"the [[Angle of attack|Angle of Attack]] (AOA) is an aerodynamic parameter that is key to understanding the limits of airplane performance. Recent accidents and incidents have resulted in new flight crew training programs, which in turn have raised interest in AOA in commercial aviation. Awareness of AOA is vitally important as the airplane nears stall.\"<ref name=\"Boeing_AOA\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_12/aoa.pdf|title=Angle of attack|year=2000|website=Aero magazine - Issue 12|publisher=Boeing|access-date= 2019-07-27| layurl=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/aeromagazine/aero_12/}}</ref> [[Chesley Sullenberger]] said AoA indicators might have helped in these two crashes. \"It is ironic that most modern aircraft measure (angle of attack) and that information is often used in many aircraft systems, but it is not displayed to pilots. Instead, pilots must infer (angle of attack) from other parameters, deducing it indirectly.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/business/article/Did-Boeing-aviation-industry-heed-lessons-of-14369021.php|title=Did Boeing, aviation industry heed lessons of 2009 Air France crash?|last=Leinfelder|first=Andrea|date=2019-08-22|work=[[Houston Chronicle]]|access-date=2019-09-01}}</ref> \n\n==== AoA sensors ====\nThough there are two sensors on the MAX only one of them is used at a time to trigger MCAS activation on the 737 MAX. Any fault in this sensor, perhaps due to physical damage,<ref name=\"sullysullenberger.com\"/> creates a [[single point of failure|single point failure]]: the flight control system lacks any basis for rejecting its input as faulty information.\n\nReports of a single point of failure were not always acknowledged by Boeing. Addressing American Airlines pilots, Boeing vice-president Mike Sinnett contradicted reports that the MCAS had a single-point failure, because the pilots themselves are the backup. Reporter Useem said in [[The Atlantic]] it was \"showing both a misunderstanding of the term and a sharp break from Boeing's long-standing practice of having multiple backups for every flight system\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/ideas/archive/2019/11/how-boeing-lost-its-bearings/602188/|title=The Long-Forgotten Flight That Sent Boeing Off Course|last=Useem|first=Jerry|date=2019-11-20|website=The Atlantic|access-date=2019-11-24}}</ref>\n\nProblems with the AoA sensor had been reported in over 200 incident reports submitted to the FAA; however, Boeing did not flight test a scenario in which it malfunctioned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/30/politics/boeing-sensor-737-max-faa/index.html|title=Boeing relied on single sensor for 737 Max that had been flagged 216 times to FAA|author1=Curt Devine |author2=Drew Griffin|website=[[CNN]]|access-date=2019-09-26}}</ref>\n\nThe sensors themselves are under scrutiny. Sensors on the Lion air aircraft were supplied by United Technologies' Rosemount Aerospace.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/economy/sensor-cited-as-potential-factor-in-boeing-crashes-draws-scrutiny/2019/03/17/5ecf0b0e-4682-11e9-aaf8-4512a6fe3439_story.html |title=Sensor cited as potential factor in Boeing crashes draws scrutiny|last=Frankel|first=Todd C.|date=2019-03-17|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2019, the EASA said it prefers triple-redundant AoA sensors rather than the dual redundancy in Boeing's proposed upgrade to the MAX.<ref name=\":18\" /> Installation of a third sensor could be expensive and take a long time. The change, if mandated, could be extended to thousands of older model 737s in service around the world.<ref name=\":18\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/european-regulator-plans-its-own-test-flights-of-boeing-737-max-in-sign-of-differences-with-faa/|title=European regulator plans its own test flights of Boeing 737 MAX in sign of rift with FAA|date=2019-09-10|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-09-11|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref>\n\nA former professor at [[Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University]], Andrew Kornecki, who is an expert in redundancy systems, said operating with one or two sensors \"would be fine if all the pilots were sufficiently trained in how to assess and handle the plane in the event of a problem\". But, he would much prefer building the plane with three sensors, as Airbus does.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/a-lack-of-redundancies-on-737-max-system-has-baffled-even-those-who-worked-on-the-jet/|title=Lack of redundancies on Boeing 737 MAX system baffles some involved in developing the jet|date=2019-03-26|first1=Mike |last1=Baker |first2=Dominic |last2=Gates|work=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-08-04}}</ref>\n\n==== AoA Disagree alert ====\nIn November 2017, after several months of MAX deliveries, Boeing discovered that the <span style=\"font-variant: small-caps;\">''AoA Disagree''</span> message, which is indicative of potential sensor mismatch on the [[primary flight display]],<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/03/27/boeing-presents-mcas-fix-to-pilots-regulators-and-media/|title=Boeing presents MCAS fix to pilots, regulators and media|last=Fehrm|first=Bjorn|date=2019-03-27|website=Leeham News and Analysis|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref> was unintentionally disabled.<ref name=\":12\" />\n\nClint Balog, a professor at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University, said after the Lion Air crash: \"In retrospect, clearly it would have been wise to include the warning as standard equipment and fully inform and train operators on MCAS\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-crash-boeing-aoa-idUSKCN1NZ0QL|title=Optional warning light could have aided Lion Air engineers before crash: experts|date=2018-11-30|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-11-13}}</ref> According to Bjorn Fehrm, Aeronautical and Economic Analyst at Leeham News and Analysis, \"A major contributor to the ultimate loss of JT610 is the missing AOA DISAGREE display on the pilots' displays.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/11/15/bjorns-corner-analysing-the-lion-air-jt610-crash-part-3/|title=Bjorn's Corner: Analysing the Lion Air JT610 crash, Part 3.|last=Fehrm|first=Bjorn|date=2019-11-15|website=Leeham News and Analysis|access-date=2019-11-15}}</ref>\n\nThe software depended on the presence of the visual indicator software, a paid option that was not selected most airlines. <ref name=\":53\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2019/11/18/the-case-against-boeing|title=The Case Against Boeing|last=MacGillis|first=Alec|date=2019-11-11|access-date=2019-11-11|issn=0028-792X}}</ref> For example, Air Canada, American Airlines and Westjet had purchased the disagree alert, while Air Canada and American Airlines also purchased, in addition, the [[#Visual AoA indicator|AoA value indicator]], and Lion Air had neither.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/amp/1.5065888|title=Air Canada says their 737 Max jets have all safety features Boeing sells as extras|last=|first=|date=March 21, 2019|work=CBC.ca|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|title=Optional warning light could have aided Lion Air engineers before crash: experts|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-indonesia-crash-boeing-aoa/optional-warning-light-could-have-aided-lion-air-engineers-before-crash-experts-idUSKCN1NZ0QL|date=2018-11-30|access-date=2019-11-13|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> Boeing had determined that the defect was not critical to aircraft safety or operation, and an internal [[Functional safety|safety review board]] (SRB) corroborated Boeing's prior assessment and its initial plan to update the aircraft in 2020. Boeing did not disclose the defect to the FAA until November 2018, in the wake of the Lion Air crash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-boeing-737-max-safety-alert-20190607-story.html|title=Boeing wanted to wait three years to fix safety alert on 737 Max|date=2019-06-07|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-08-03|agency=Associated Press}}</ref>\n<ref name=\"Boeing AOA Disagree Alert\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/05/05/business/boeing-737-max-warning-light.html|title=Boeing Believed a 737 Max Warning Light Was Standard. It Wasn't.|last=Gelles|first=David|date=2019-05-05|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-08-27|last2=Kitroeff|first2=Natalie|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/03/21/business/boeing-safety-features-charge.html|title=Doomed Boeing Jets Lacked 2 Safety Features That Company Sold Only as Extras|last=Tabuchi|first=Hiroko|date=2019-03-21|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-08-27|last2=Gelles|first2=David|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Consequently, Southwest had announced to pilots that its entire fleet of MAX 8 aircraft will receive the optional upgrades.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/southwest-airlines-is-adding-new-angle-of-attack-indicators-to-its-737-max-fleet/|title=Southwest is adding new Angle of Attack indicators to its 737 Max fleet|date=2018-11-30|website=The Air Current|access-date=2019-06-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aviationtoday.com/2018/11/30/lion-air-report-analyzes-pilot-struggle-737-max-trim-system/|title=Lion Air Report Analyzes Pilot Struggle With 737 MAX Trim System|date=2018-11-30|website=Avionics|access-date=2019-07-15}}</ref> In March 2019, after the second accident of Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302, a Boeing representative told ''[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]'' magazine, \"Customers have been informed that AOA disagree alert will become a standard feature on the 737 Max. It can be retrofitted on previously delivered airplanes.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inc.com/minda-zetlin/boeing-safety-features-options-upgrades-angle-attack-disagree-light-mcas-lion-air-ethiopian.html|title=Boeing CEO Says Safety Is Highest Priority. The Company's Pricing Says Something Different|last=Zetlin|first=Minda|date=2019-03-24|website=[[Inc. (magazine)|Inc.]]|access-date=2019-07-27}}</ref>\n\nOn May 5, 2019, ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'' reported that Boeing had known of existing problems with the flight control system a year before the Lion Air accident.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/boeing-knew-about-safety-alert-problem-for-a-year-before-telling-faa-airlines-11557087129|title=Boeing Knew About Safety-Alert Problem for a Year Before Telling FAA, Airlines|last=Pasztor|first=Andy|date=May 5, 2019|work=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=December 24, 2019|last2=Tangel|first2=Andrew|last3=Sider|first3=Alison|author-link1=Andy Pasztor|url-access=subscription}}</ref> Boeing defended that \"Neither the angle of attack indicator nor the AoA Disagree alert are necessary for the safe operation of the airplane.\" Boeing recognized that the defective software was not implemented to their specifications as a \"standard, standalone feature.\" Boeing stated, \"...MAX production aircraft will have an activated and operable AOA Disagree alert and an optional angle of attack indicator. All customers with previously delivered MAX airplanes will have the ability to activate the AOA Disagree alert.\"<ref name=\"Boeing AOA Disagree Alert\" /> Boeing CEO Muilenburg said the company's communication about the alert \"was not consistent. And that's unacceptable.\"<ref name=\"voanews_20190616_warning\">{{cite news |url= https://www.voanews.com/usa/boeing-ceo-admits-mistake-handling-warning-system-problem |title= Boeing CEO Admits Mistake in Handling Warning-System Problem |agency= Associated Press |date= June 16, 2019 |via= [[Voice of America|VOA]]}}</ref><ref name=\"Boeing AOA Disagree Alert\">{{cite press release |url= https://boeing.mediaroom.com/news-releases-statements?item=130431 |title= Boeing Statement on AOA Disagree Alert |publisher= Boeing |date= 2019-05-05 |access-date=May 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==== Visual AoA indicator ====\n[[File:Primary Flight Display of a Boeing 737-800.png|thumb|250px|upright|The [[primary flight display]] of a Boeing 737-800 aircraft with a functional [[angle of attack]] display on the upper right; the AoA Disagree alert would appear as a text message.]]\n\nBoeing published an article in ''Aero'' magazine about AoA systems, \"Operational use of Angle of Attack on modern commercial jet planes\": {{quote| The AOA indicator can be used to assist with unreliable airspeed indications as a result of blocked [[Pitot tube|pitot]] or static ports and may provide additional situation and configuration awareness to the flight crew.<ref name=\"Boeing_AOA\" />}}\n\nBoeing announced a change in policy in the Frequently Asked Questions in a ([[FAQ]]) about the MAX corrective work, \"With the software update, customers are not charged for the AOA disagree feature or their selection of the AOA indicator option.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-contacts.page|title=Frequently Asked Questions|publisher=Boeing: 737 MAX FAQ}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, the NTSB issued Safety Recommendation A-96-094. <blockquote>TO THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION (FAA): ''Require that all transport-category aircraft present pilots with angle-of-attack info in a visual format, and that all air carriers train their pilots to use the info to obtain maximum possible airplane climb performance.''\n</blockquote>\n\nThe NTSB also stated about another accident in 1997, that \"a display of angle of attack on the flight deck would have maintained the flightcrew's awareness of the stall condition and it would have provided direct indication of the pitch attitudes required for recovery throughout the attempted stall recovery sequence.\" The NTSB also believed that the accident may have been prevented if a direct indication of AoA was presented to the flightcrew (NTSB, 1997).\"<ref>{{Cite report |url=https://ntrs.nasa.gov/search.jsp?R=20140011419 |title=Review of Research On Angle-of-Attack Indicator Effectiveness |last=Le Vie |first=Lisa R. |publisher=NASA [[Langley Research Center]] (LaRC) |date=August 1, 2014 |id=NASA/TM\u20132014-218514 |hdl=2060/20140011419}}{{PD-notice}}</ref>{{rp|page=29}}\n\n=== Flight computer architecture ===\nIn early April 2019, Boeing reported a problem with software affecting flaps and other flight-control hardware, unrelated to MCAS; classified as critical to flight safety, the FAA has ordered Boeing to fix the problem correspondingly.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/africa/ethiopia-says-pilots-performed-boeings-recommendations-to-stop-doomed-aircraft-from-diving-urges-review-of-737-max-flight-control-system/2019/04/04/3a125942-4fec-11e9-bdb7-44f948cc0605_story.html|title=Additional software problem detected in Boeing 737 Max flight control system, officials say|first1=Aaron C. |last1=Davis |first2=Luz |last2=Lazo |first3=Paul |last3=Schemm |date=April 4, 2019|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=April 4, 2019}}</ref>\nIn October 2019, the EASA has suggested to conduct more testing on proposed revisions to flight-control computers due to its concerns about portions of proposed fixes to MCAS.<ref name=\"EASA on proposed fixes\">{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/friction-between-u-s-european-regulators-could-delay-737-max-return-to-service-11570527001|title=Friction Between U.S., European Regulators Could Delay 737 MAX Return to Service |last1=Pasztor|first1=Andy|author-link1=Andy Pasztor|last2=Tangel|first2=Andrew|date=October 8, 2019|newspaper=[[The Wall Street Journal]]|access-date=October 8, 2019|url-access=subscription }}</ref>\nThe necessary changes to improve redundancy between the two flight control computers have proved more complex and time-consuming than the fixes for the original MCAS issue, delaying any re-introduction to service beyond the date originally envisaged.<ref name=\"levin\"/>\n\n<!-- Flight computer start-up verification and self-diagnostics -->\nIn January 2020, new software issues were discovered, affecting monitoring of the flight computer start-up process and verifying readiness for flight.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.slashgear.com/boeing-finds-yet-another-737-max-software-issue-19607147/|title=Boeing finds yet another 737 MAX software issue|date=2020-01-19|website=SlashGear|access-date=2020-01-20}}</ref>\n\n==== Microprocessor stress testing ====\nThe MAX systems are integrated in the \"e-cab\" test flight deck, a simulator built for developing the MAX.<ref name=\":51\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/news/the-e-cab-a-test-flight-deck.page|title=Boeing: The \"e-cab\" \u2013 a test flight deck|website=www.boeing.com|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref><ref name=\":52\">{{Cite web|url=http://players.brightcove.net/800000612001/a7975ab0-d4c3-4514-a6c3-d7bfff0667c5_default/index.html?videoId=4637926975001|title=The \"e-cab\" \u2013 A Test Flight Deck|last=|first=|date=2015-11-30|website=players.brightcove.net|publisher=Boeing|access-date=2019-10-22}}</ref> In June 2019, \"in a special Boeing simulator that is designed for engineering reviews,\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-boeing-737-max-new-glitch-20190627-story.html|title=Boeing needs up to three months to fix newly discovered 737 Max glitch|first=Alan |last=Levin |first2=Julie |last2=Johnsson |first3=Shaun |last3=Courtney|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|access-date=2019-07-04}}</ref> FAA pilots performed a [[Stress testing (software)|stress testing]] scenario{{snd}}an abnormal condition identified through [[Failure mode and effects analysis|FMEA]] after the MCAS update was implemented<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fehrm |first1=Bjorn |title=New pitch trim issue forces further changes to 737 MAX software |url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/06/28/bjorns-corner-new-pitch-trim-issue-forces-further-changes-to-737-max-software/ |work=Leeham News and Analysis |date=June 28, 2019}}</ref>{{snd}}for evaluating the effect of a fault in a microprocessor: as expected from the scenario, the horizontal stabilizer pointed the nose downward. Although the test pilot ultimately recovered control, the system was slow to respond to the proper runaway stabilizer checklist steps. Boeing initially classified this as a \"major\" hazard, and the FAA upgraded it to a much more severe \"catastrophic\" rating. Boeing stated that the issue can be fixed in software.<ref name=\"Boeing 737 MAX software\">{{cite press release|url=https://boeing.mediaroom.com/2019-06-26-Boeing-Statement-on-737-MAX-software|title=Boeing Statement on 737 MAX software|publisher=Boeing|date=June 26, 2019|access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> The software change will not be ready for evaluation until at least September 2019.<ref name=\"aircurrent20190627\">{{cite news |last1=Ostrower |first1=Jon |title=FAA and Boeing initially disagreed on severity of \"catastrophic\" 737 Max software glitch |url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/faa-and-boeing-initially-disagreed-on-severity-of-catastrophic-737-max-software-glitch/ |work=The Air Current |date=June 27, 2019}}</ref> EASA director Patrick Ky said that retrofitting additional hardware is an option to be considered.<ref name=\"bloomberg-20190705\" />\n\nEarly news reports were inaccurate in attributing the problem to an [[Intel 80286|80286]]<ref>{{cite news |last1=Allard |first1=Andr\u00e9 |title=MAX's computer has reached its limit |url=https://www.wingsoverquebec.com/?p=8649 |work=Wings Over Qu\u00e9bec |date=July 3, 2019 }}</ref> microprocessor overwhelmed with data. The test scenario simulated an event toggling five bits in the flight control computer. The bits represent status flags such as whether MCAS is active, or whether the tail trim motor is energized. Engineers were able to simulate [[single event upset]]s and artificially induce MCAS activation by manipulating these signals. Such a fault occurs when memory bits change from 0 to 1 or vice versa, which is something that can be caused by cosmic rays striking the microprocessor.<ref name=\"Seattle Times 20190801\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/newly-stringent-faa-tests-spur-a-fundamental-software-redesign-of-737-max-flight-controls/|title=Newly stringent FAA tests spur a fundamental software redesign of Boeing's 737 MAX flight controls|date=2019-08-01|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-08-02|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref>\n\nThe failure scenario was known before the MAX entered service in 2017: it had been assessed in a safety analysis when the plane was certified. Boeing had concluded that pilots could perform a procedure to shut off the motor driving the stabilizer to overcome the nose-down movement.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-07-27/latest-737-max-fault-that-alarmed-test-pilots-rooted-in-software|title=Latest 737 Max Fault That Alarmed Test Pilots Rooted in Software|publisher=Bloomberg News}}</ref> The scenario also affects [[Boeing 737 Next Generation|737NG]] aircraft, though it presents less risk than on the MAX. On the NG, moving the [[Yoke (aeronautics)|yoke]] counters any uncommanded stabilizer input, but this function is bypassed on the MAX to avoid negating the purpose of MCAS.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://aviationweek.com/commercial-aviation/software-fix-will-address-most-recent-max-issue|title=Software Fix Will Address Most Recent MAX Issue|last1=Broderick|first1=Sean|date=August 1, 2019|work=Aviation Week & Space Technology}}</ref> Boeing also said that it agreed with additional requirements that the FAA required it to fulfill, and added that it was working toward resolving the safety risk. It will not offer the MAX for certification until all requirements have been satisfied.<ref name=\"Boeing 737 MAX software\" />\n\n==== Computer redundancy ====\n{{As of|2019}}, the two flight control computers of Boeing 737 never cross-checked each other's operations; i.e., each was a single non-redundant channel. This lack of robustness existed since the early implementation and persisted for decades.<ref name=\"Seattle Times 20190801\" /> The updated flight control system will use both flight control computers and compare their outputs. This switch to a [[fail-safe]] two-channel [[Redundancy (engineering)|redundant]] system, with each computer using an independent set of sensors, is a radical change from the architecture used on 737s since the introduction on the older model 737\u2013300 in the 1980s. Up to the MAX in its prior to groundings version, the system alternates between computers after each flight.<ref name=\"Seattle Times 20190801\" /> The two computers architecture allowed switching in flight if the operating computer failed, thus increasing availability. In the revised architecture, Boeing required the two computers to monitor each other so that each one can vet the other.<ref name=\"levin\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2019-11-08/delays-in-boeing-max-return-began-with-near-crash-in-simulator|title=Delays in Boeing Max Return Began With Near-Crash in Simulator|last=Levin|first=Alan|date=2019-11-08|website=www.bloomberg.com|access-date=2019-11-09}}</ref>\n\n==== Trim system malfunction indicator ====\nIn January 2020, during flight testing, Boeing discovered a problem with an indicator light; the defect was traced to the \"redesign the two flight computers that control the 737 Max to make them more resilient to failure\".  The indicator, which signals a problem with the trim system, can be turned on longer than intended by design.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Boeing Fixing New Software Bug on Max; Key Test Flight Nears|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-02-06/boeing-identifies-new-software-problem-on-grounded-737-max-jet|date=2020-02-06|work=Bloomberg}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theverge.com/2020/2/6/21126364/boeing-737-max-software-glitch-flaw-problem|title=Boeing finds another software problem on the 737 Max|last=O'Kane|first=Sean|date=2020-02-06|website=The Verge|access-date=2020-02-07}}</ref>\n\n\n=== Runaway stabilizer and manual trim ===\nIn February 2016, the EASA certified the MAX with the expectation that pilot procedures and training would clearly explain unusual situations in which the seldom used manual trim wheel would be required to trim the plane, i.e. adjust the angle of the nose; however, the original flight manual did not mention those situations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.easa.europa.eu/sites/default/files/dfu/IM.A.120%20Boeing737%20TCDS%20APPENDIX%20ISS%2010.pdf|title=Explanatory Note to TCDS IM.A.120 \u2013 Boeing 737|date=May 24, 2019|website=[[European Union Aviation Safety Agency]] (EASA)|access-date=}}</ref> The EASA certification document referred to simulations whereby the electric thumb switches were ineffective to properly trim the MAX under certain conditions. The EASA document said that after flight testing, because the thumb switches could not always control trim on their own, the FAA was concerned by whether the 737 MAX system complied with regulations.<ref name=\":23\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-ethiopia-airplane-regulator-insight-idUSKCN1RA0DP|title=Regulators knew before crashes that 737 MAX trim control was confusing in some conditions: document|work=Reuters|access-date=2019-09-17}}</ref> The American Airlines flight manual contains a similar notice regarding the thumb switches but does not specify conditions where the manual wheel may be needed.<ref name=\":23\" />\n\nBoeing's CEO Muilenburg, when asked about the non-disclosure of MCAS, cited the \"runaway stabilizer trim\" procedure as part of the training manual. He added that Boeing's bulletin pointed to that existing flight procedure. Boeing views the \"runaway stabilizer trim\" checklist as a memory item for pilots. Mike Sinnett, vice president and general manager for the Boeing New Mid-Market Airplane (NMA) since July 2019, repeatedly described the procedure as a \"memory item\".<ref name=\":34\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeings-emergency-procedure-for-737-max-may-have-failed-on-ethiopian-flight/|title=Why Boeing's emergency directions may have failed to save 737 MAX|date=2019-04-03|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-09-27|last=Gates|first=Dominic}}</ref> However, some airlines view it as an item for the quick reference card.<ref name=\":35\">{{Cite web|url=https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/checklists-come-into-focus-as-pace-setter-for-737-max-return/|title=Checklists come into focus as pace-setter for 737 Max return|date=2019-10-09|website=The Air Current|access-date=2019-10-09}}</ref> The FAA issued a recommendation about memory items in an Advisory Circular, ''Standard Operating Procedures and Pilot Monitoring Duties for Flight Deck Crewmembers'': \"Memory items should be avoided whenever possible. If the procedure must include memory items, they should be clearly identified, emphasized in training, less than three items, and should not contain conditional decision steps.\"<ref name=\":36\">{{Cite book|url=https://www.faa.gov/documentlibrary/media/advisory_circular/ac_120-71b.pdf|title=Standard Operating Procedures and Pilot Monitoring Duties for Flight Deck Crewmembers|date=January 10, 2017|publisher=FAA|isbn=|series=Advisory Circulars|location=|pages=|id=AC 120-71B}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, Boeing told airlines that MCAS could not be overcome by pulling back on the control column to stop a runaway trim as on previous generation 737s.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/03/world/asia/lion-air-plane-crash-pilots.html|title=After a Lion Air 737 Max Crashed in October, Questions About the Plane Arose|last=Glanz|first=James|date=2019-02-03|work=[[The New York Times]]|access-date=2019-07-27|last2=Creswell|first2=Julie|issn=0362-4331|last3=Kaplan|first3=Thomas|last4=Wichter|first4=Zach}}</ref> Nevertheless, confusion continued: the safety committee of a major U.S. airline misled its pilots by telling that the MCAS could be overcome by \"applying opposite control-column input to activate the column cutout switches\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://aviationweek.com/boeing-737-max-what-happened-and-what-now|title=Boeing 737 MAX: What Happened, And What Now?|publisher=Aviation Week Network|access-date=2019-08-22}}</ref> Former pilot and [[CBS Corporation|CBS]] aviation & safety expert [[Chesley Sullenberger]] testified, \"The logic was that when MCAS was activated, it had to be, and must not be prevented.\"<ref name=\"sullysullenberger.com\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.sullysullenberger.com/my-testimony-today-before-the-house-subcommittee-on-aviation/|title=My Testimony Today Before the House Subcommittee on Aviation|date=2019-06-19|website=Sully Sullenberger|access-date=2019-06-20}}</ref> In October, Sullenberger wrote, \"These emergencies did not present as a classic runaway stabilizer problem, but initially as ambiguous unreliable airspeed and altitude situations, masking MCAS.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sullysullenberger.com/my-letter-to-the-editor-of-new-york-times-magazine/|title=My Letter to the Editor of New York Times Magazine|date=2019-10-13|website=Sully Sullenberger|access-date=2019-10-14}}</ref>\n\nIn a legal complaint against Boeing, the Southwest Airlines Pilot Association states:<ref>{{Cite book|title=PLAINTIFF'S ORIGINAL PETITION, SWAPA vs. Boeing|last=|first=|publisher=|year=2019|isbn=|location=|pages=}}</ref><blockquote>An MCAS failure is not like a runaway stabilizer. A runaway stabilizer has continuous un-commanded movement of the tail, whereas MCAS is not continuous and pilots (theoretically) can counter the nose-down movement, after which MCAS would move the aircraft tail down again. Moreover, unlike runaway stabilizer, MCAS disables the control column response that 737 pilots have grown accustomed to and relied upon in earlier generations of 737 aircraft.</blockquote>\n\nIn May 2019, ''[[The Seattle Times]]'' reported that the two stabilizer cutoff switches on the MAX operate differently than on the earlier 737 NG. On previous aircraft, one cutoff switch deactivates the thumb buttons on the control yoke that pilots use to move the horizontal stabilizer; the other cutoff switch disables automatic control (as from autopilot) to move the stabilizer in the tail. On the MAX, both switches do the same thing: they cut off all electric power to the stabilizer, both from the yoke buttons and from an automatic system, like MCAS. With all power to the stabilizer cut, pilots have no choice but to use the mechanical trim wheel in the center console.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/boeing-altered-key-switches-in-737-max-cockpit-limiting-ability-to-shut-off-mcas/|title=Boeing altered key switches in 737 MAX cockpit, limiting ability to shut off MCAS|date=2019-05-10|website=[[The Seattle Times]]|access-date=2019-10-15}}</ref> However, as pilots pull on the 737 controls to raise the nose of the aircraft, aerodynamic forces on the elevator create an opposing force, effectively paralyzing the jackscrew mechanism.<ref\n      name=\"jscrew\">{{Cite web\n | url=              https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/vestigal-design-issue-clouds-737-max-crash-investigations/|title=Vestigal design issue clouds 737 MAX crash investigations\n | date=            2019-04-04\n    }}</ref>> It becomes very difficult for pilots to hand crank the trim wheel.<ref\n  name=\"jscrew\"/> The problem was encountered on earlier 737 versions, and a \"roller coaster\" emergency technique for handling the flight condition was documented in 1982 for the 737-200 but did not appear in training documentation for later versions (including the MAX).<ref\n  name=\"jscrew\"/>\n\nDuring the groundings, special flights to reposition MAX aircraft to storage locations, as per 14 CFR \u00a7 21.197, flew at lower [[flight level|altitude]] and with [[Flap (aeronautics)|flaps]] extended to circumvent MCAS activation, rather than using the recovery procedure after the fact. Such flights required a certain pilot qualification as well as permission from corresponding regulators, and with no other cabin crew or passengers.<ref name=\"LII / Legal Information Institute\">{{cite web |url=https://www.law.cornell.edu/cfr/text/14/21.197 |title=14 CFR \u00a7 21.197 - Special flight permits. |publisher=LII / Legal Information Institute |access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref><ref name=\"simpleflying.com\">{{Cite web|url=https://simpleflying.com/norwegian-boeing-737-max-flight/|title=Norwegian Flies Boeing 737 MAX Over Europe For Storage Purposes|date=2019-06-12|website=Simple Flying|access-date=2019-06-17}}</ref>\n\n==== Horizontal stabilizer actuator ====\nThe horizontal stabilizer is fitted with a conventional [[elevator (aeronautics)|elevator]] for flight control. However it is itself all-moving about a single pivot and can be [[trim (aircraft)|trimmed]] to adjust its angle. The trim is actuated via a [[jackscrew]] mechanism.\n\n====Slippage concern====\nSylvain Alarie and Gilles Primeau, experts on the horizontal stabilizers, observed anomalies in the data from the aircraft data recorders: a progressive shift of 0.2 degrees of the horizontal stabilizer, before the crash. \"It may not seem like much, but it is an order of magnitude higher than what is normally allowed when designing systems like these\", says Gilles Primeau. They say that the movements are easily observable, and disallowed according to Regulation 395A. These anomalies raise fundamental questions about this jack screw, which controls the horizontal stabilizer since the beginning of the 737 models, first certified in 1967.<ref name=\":19\">{{Cite web|url=https://ici.radio-canada.ca/nouvelle/1382157/boeing-737-max-experts-questions-enquete-verin-systeme-anomalie-aeronautique|title=Des r\u00e9v\u00e9lations troublantes sur le Boeing 737 MAX 8|last=ICI.Radio-Canada.ca|first=Zone \u00c9conomie-|website=Radio-Canada.ca|language=fr-ca|access-date=2019-11-11}}</ref>\n\nThese slips are particularly visible on flight ET302: \"While there is no MCAS command, and no control of the pilots, we see a movement of the jack screw which controls the horizontal stabilizer, we see a slip. And at the very end of the flight, the jack screw starts to slide again with an increase in the speed of the plane and its dive,\" says Alarie.<ref name=\":19\" />\n\nSince its original design, the 737 has become 61% heavier, 24% longer, and 40% wider, and its engines twice as powerful.\nThese experts are concerned that the loads on the jack screw have potentially increased since the creation of the 737. By regulations, the controls must be designed for 125% of the foreseeable loads.<ref name=\":19\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://airinsight.com/more-bad-news-for-boeing-over-the-weekend/|title=November 2019: More Bad News for Boeing over the Weekend|date=2019-11-11|access-date=2019-11-11|website=airinsight.com|last=Arvai|first=Ernest}}\n</ref> These experts have raised concerns about the motors possibly overheating in April 2019.<ref>{{Cite news| title=Boeing a-t-il fait preuve de n\u00e9gligence?|trans-title=Was Boeing negligent?|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=BbY5P-ylYS4|language=fr|access-date=2019-11-14|last=|first=|date=April 1, 2019|publisher=Radio-Canada info}}</ref>\n\n====Manual trim stiffness====\nIn the early 1980s a problem was found with the 737-200 model. When the elevator operated to raise or lower the nose, it set up a strong force on the trim jackscrew which opposed any corrective force from the control systems. When attempting to correct an unwanted deflection using the manual trim wheel, exerting enough hand force to overcome the force exerted by the elevator became increasingly difficult as speed and deflection increased and the jack screw effectively jammed in place.<ref name=\"ostrower\">Jon Ostrower; \"[https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/vestigal-design-issue-clouds-737-max-crash-investigations/ Vestigial design issue clouds 737 Max crash investigations]\", ''The Air Current'', April 4, 2019. (retrieved November 21, 2019)</ref>\n\nA workaround was developed called the \"roller coaster\" technique. Counter-intuitively, to correct an excessive deflection causing a dive the pilot first pushes the nose down further, before easing back to gently raise the nose again. During this easing back period, the elevator deflection reduces or even reverses, its force on the jackscrew does likewise and the manual trim eases up. The workaround was included in the pilot's emergency procedures and in the training schedule.<ref name=\"ostrower\"/>\n\nHowever while the 737 Max has a similar jackscrew mechanism the \"roller coaster\" technique has been dropped from the pilot information. During the events leading to the two Max crashes, the stiffness of the manual trim wheel repeatedly prevented manual trim adjustment to correct the MCAS-induced nose-down pitching. The issue has been brought to the notice of the DoJ criminal inquiry into the 737 Max crashes.<ref name=\"ostrower\"/>\n\nIn simulator tests of [[Ethiopian Airlines Flight 302]] flight scenario, the trim wheel was \"impossible\" to move when one of the pilots would instinctively pull up from the nosedives. It takes 15 turns to manually trim the aircraft one degree, and up to 40 turns to bring the trim back to neutral from the nose down position caused by MCAS.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.flightglobal.com/safety/simulator-tests-demonstrate-737-max-manual-trim-difficulties/137651.article|title=Simulator tests demonstrate 737 Max manual trim difficulties|last=Hemmerdinger2020-04-02T16:49:00+01:00|first=Jon|website=Flight Global|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>  \n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{cite video |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=QytfYyHmxtc |title= Rogue Boeing 737 Max planes \u2018with minds of their own\u2019 |author= 60 Minutes Australia |date= May 5, 2019 |via= YouTube |quote= MCAS was designed using data from only one of the sensors because we knew the FAA would not have certified a two sensor system without level D [simulator] training}}\n* {{cite video |url= https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=H2tuKiiznsY|title=The real reason Boeing's new plane crashed twice |author= [[Vox (website)#Video|Vox Videos]] |date= Apr 15, 2019|via= Youtube}}\n* {{Cite video |author= Mentour Pilot|title=Boeing 737 Unable to Trim!! Cockpit video (Full flight sim)|date=2019-04-19|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aoNOVlxJmow|via= Youtube}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* {{Cite web |url= https://www.boeing.com/commercial/737max/737-max-software-updates.page |title= The 737 MAX MCAS Software Enhancement |publisher= Boeing}}\n* {{cite news |url= https://www.washingtonpost.com/business/2019/05/06/safety-was-just-given-inside-boeings-boardroom-amid-max-crisis/ |title= 'Safety was just a given': Inside Boeing's boardroom amid the 737 Max crisis |author= Douglas MacMillan |date= May 5, 2019 |work= Washington Post}}\n* {{cite news |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/engineers-say-boeing-pushed-to-limit-safety-testing-in-race-to-certify-planes-including-737-max/ |title= Engineers say Boeing pushed to limit safety testing in race to certify planes, including 737 MAX |date= May 5, 2019 |author1= Dominic Gates |author2= Mike Baker |work= The Seattle Times}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://leehamnews.com/2019/10/04/bjorns-corner-fly-by-steel-or-electrical-wire-part-11/ | title=Bjorn\u2019s Corner: Fly by steel or electrical wire, Part 11|last=|date=2019-10-04|website=Leeham News and Analysis|language=en-US|access-date=2019-10-07}} Design of a pitch stability augmentation system.\n* {{cite news |url= https://theaircurrent.com/aviation-safety/new-document-in-737-max-investigation-points-to-chaos-pressure-in-mcas-development/ |title= New document in 737 Max investigation points to chaos, pressure in MCAS development |date= Oct 18, 2019 |author= Jon Ostrower |work= The Air Current}}\n\n{{Boeing}}\n\n[[Category:Boeing]]\n[[Category:Aircraft controls]]\n", "name_user": "Marc Lacoste", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eManual trim stiffness:date is more important than access-date for dated releases.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maneuvering_Characteristics_Augmentation_System"}
{"title_page": "Jernail Singh Anand", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=June 2018}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Jernail Singh Anand\n| image              = [[File:Jernail Singh Poet.png|250px]]\n| alt                = <!-- descriptive text for use by speech synthesis (text-to-speech) software -->\n| caption            = \n| birth_name         = <!-- only use if different from name -->\n| birth_date         = 1955\n| birth_place        = Ludhiana, Punjab\n| death_date         = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (DEATH date then BIRTH date)  -->\n| death_place        = \n| nationality        = [[Indian people|Indian]]\n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = Poet, Author, Philosopher, Spiritualist, Enviornmentalist\n| years_active       = \n| known_for          = \n| notable_works      = \n}}\n\n'''Jernail Singh Anand''' is a poet.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://jamiededes.com/2017/10/19/dr-jernail-s-anand-poet-writing-in-the-virtual-world-by-aprilia-zank-ph-d/|title=\"Dr. Jernail S. Anand (Poet), Writing in the Virtual World\" by Aprilia Zank, Ph.D.|date=2017-10-19|work=THE POET BY DAY|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://verbumlandiart.com/dr-jernail-singh-anand-a-philosopher-of-language-life-and-literature-essay-of-italian-poetess-claudia-piccinno/|title=Dr JERNAIL SINGH ANAND \u2026.a philosopher of Language Life and Literature / Essay of Italian poetess Claudia Piccinno \u2013 VERBUMLANDIART|website=verbumlandiof Maharaja Ranjit Singh College, art.com|language=it-IT|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref> Anand has authored 65 books of English Poetry, fiction, [[non-fiction]] and spirituality.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://atunispoetry.com/2016/09/14/dr-jernail-s-anand/|title=Dr. Jernail S. ANAND|date=2016-09-14|work=Galaktika Poetike  \"ATUNIS\"|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bol.com/nl/p/a-million-destinies/9200000014175757/|title= A Million Destinies [Poems], Dr Jernail Singh Anand {{!}} 9781484831342 {{!}} Boeken|website=www.bol.com|language=nl-NL|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref> He was awarded a Ph. D. in English by Panjab University Chandigarh  in year 2000. He is a environmentalist and a column writer. He retired as Principal and is now on an Honorary Position of Professor Emeritus at Institute of European Roma Studies and Research, Crimes Against Humanity and International Law, Belgrade, Serbia. Dr Anand has co-innovated the theory of Bio-Text in Critical Theory along with an Iranian Scholar, Dr Roghaye Farsi. He Was President of The World Poetry Conference Organized in October 2019 in Bathinda Punjab, India. <ref>{{Cite book|last=Dayal,|first=Dr Deen|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=dxlgDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT655&lpg=PT655&dq=%22Philosophique+Poetica%22&source=bl&ots=GCpzYSaWD7&sig=ACfU3U3O66uQMSyFz4yMX9ex1f6pCMN1hA&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjSmb3fyvzjAhVSSX0KHRnyAlUQ6AEwDXoECAkQAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Philosophique%20Poetica%22&f=false|title=Complexion Based Discriminations: Global Insights|publisher=Notion Press|year=|isbn=9781643242323|location=|pages=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://atunispoetry.com/2019/07/01/world-poetry-conference-poet-in-the-service-of-mankind-philosophique-poetica-and-grand-productions-canada-world-poetry-conference-13th-and-14-th-october-2019/|title=World Poetry Conference: Poet in the service of mankind conference 13th and 14th October 2019|last=Agronsh|first=Agronsh|date=2019-07-01|website=ATUNIS|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.worldliterature.in/|title=Philosophique Poetica|last=Aggarwal|first=S|date=2019-08-12|website=World Literature India|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-08-12}}</ref>  \n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in 1955 at [[Ludhiana, Punjab, India|Ludhiana, Punjab]] and grew up at native village Longowal in the Sangrur, Punjab, Anand graduated from Govt. College, Ludhiana, and earned his Masters in English Literature from [[Punjabi University]], [[Patiala]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://atunispoetry.com/2016/07/06/the-interview-of-dr-j-s-anand-with-the-turkish-tv-building-bridges/|title=The Interview of Dr J.S. Anand with the Turkish TV. Building Bridges.|date=2016-07-06|work=Galaktika Poetike \"ATUNIS\"|access-date=2018-04-30|language=en-US}}</ref> Punjab University, Chandigarh conferred on him degree of Doctor of Philosophy in 2000 for his work on mysticism in the poetry of [[Walt Whitman]] and [[Puran Singh|Prof. Puran Singh]].\n\n==Career==\nAnand began his career as Lecturer in English at [[Gujranwala Guru Nanak Khalsa College|GGN Khalsa College]], Ludhiana. Then he became the Principal at DAV College, Bathinda and served there for 10 years. He co-founded World Foundation for Peace and was National Vice-President of International Human Rights Observatory in 2013 .  In 2016, he was called by the World Union of Poets [Italy]  to serve as the President of the Jury of their 2016 awards.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.boloji.com/articles/49111/beyond-life-beyond-death|title=Beyond Life Beyond Death  by Durga Patva|work=Boloji|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>\n\nHe represented India at the Kibatek 39 Poetry Festival organized by the Pablo Naruda Literary Association, Taranto, Italy held in February 2016. He represented India at the World Institute of Peace Nigeria organized World Peace Seminar in Nov. 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.wnwu.org/index.php/en/our-members/188-chief-advisor-to-the-president-of-the-world-nations-writars-union-in-kazakhstan-on-contemporary-world-literature-3|title=Chief Advisor To The President of the World Nations Writars' Union in Kazakhstan on Contemporary World Literature|last=User|first=Super|website=www.wnwu.org|language=en-gb|access-date=2018-04-30}}</ref>\n\nDuring his career, he served on the Boards of educational societies including the Senate and Syndicate of [[Punjabi University]], and Board of Studies of [[Guru Kashi University]]. Anand has authored 60 books, published 120 articles, published various national and international anthologies, and has introduced poets by writing Review Articles and Forewords for their books.\n\n==Selected bibliography==\n*{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/title/trespassers-a-novel/oclc/34851544?loc=|title=The trespassers : A Novel|last=Anand|first=J S|publisher=Writers Workshop Kolkata|year=1995|isbn=9788171898190|location=Kolkata|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.co.in/books/about/Spare_Me_O_Lucifer.html?id=ON6uHAAACAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Spare me, O Lucifer!: Poems|last=Anand|first=J S|publisher=Writers Workshop (Rebird)|year=2000|isbn=978-8175956940|location=Kolkata India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|url=https://www.isbns.co.tt/isbn/9788173413322/|title=THE SPLIT VISION|publisher=Indian Publisher Distributors|year=2004|isbn=9788173413322|location=New Delhi India|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/18100628-beyond-words-poems|title=Beyond Words [Poems]: A Psycho-Spiritual Odyssey Into the Post-Colonial Mindscape: A Psycho-Spiritual Odyssey Into the Post-Colonial Mindscape|last=Anand|first=J S|publisher=Createspace Independent Publishing Platform|year=2013|isbn=9781484097502|location=California US|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|url=https://my.justfiction-edition.com/catalog/details/store/fr/book/978-3-8454-4939-5/the-wolves-of-malwadi?search=the%20wolves%20of%20malwadi|title=The Wolves of Malwadi|last=Anand|first=J S|publisher=JustFiction Edition|year=2013|isbn=9783845449395|location=Latvia EU|pages=}}\n*.{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|url=https://www.amazon.com/MONSTER-WITHIN-non-fiction-Postmodern-Politico-societal/dp/1490932879|title=The Monster Within: A Postmodern Critique of the Politico-societal living systems (2nd Ed.)|publisher=Createspace Independent Publishing Platform|year=2013|isbn=9781490932873|location=California US|pages=}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Anand|first=J S|url=https:/